// Unit 25: Die Uni
// Level: B2

const UNIT_25 =
{n:25,lang:"de",srcLang:"en",track:"v2",title:"Die Uni",sub:"Herr Professor Doktor",icon:"🎓",level:"B2.1",color:"#7B5EE8",lessons:[
{id:"deu_r25l1",title:"Herr Professor Doktor",icon:"\uD83C\uDFDB\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Herr Professor Doktor",desc:"Freie Universität Berlin, Dahlem. October. Verumius enters the world of the German university. Learn the key campus words and discover what makes German university culture unique.",goals:["Learn 20 words about university life","Discover the academic register of German","Follow Verumius on his first day on campus"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-fub-dahlem-campus",trg:"Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin, Dahlem. Ein Oktobermorgen. Die Geb\u00e4ude der 1960er stehen zwischen alten Platanen. Studenten radeln mit Kaffeebechern vorbei. Schwarze Bretter quellen \u00fcber vor Flyern. Verumius h\u00e4lt einen Campusplan in der Hand und dreht ihn auf den Kopf.",src:"Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin, Dahlem. An October morning. The 1960s buildings stand between old plane trees. Students cycle past with coffee cups. Bulletin boards overflow with flyers. Verumius holds a campus map and turns it upside down."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"nervous",art:"de-fub-dahlem-campus",trg:"Entschuldigung, wo ist der H\u00f6rsaal 1A? Ich habe gleich meine erste Vorlesung.",src:"Excuse me, where is lecture hall 1A? I have my first lecture in a moment."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"amused",art:"de-fub-dahlem-campus",trg:"Ein Student zeigt nach links. Verumius geht nach rechts. Ein anderer Student dirigiert ihn zur\u00fcck. Deutsche Universit\u00e4tscampus haben kein Erbarmen mit Neuank\u00f6mmlingen.",src:"A student points left. Verumius walks right. Another student redirects him. German university campuses have no mercy for newcomers."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"thinking",art:"de-fub-dahlem-campus",trg:"H\u00e4tte ich doch den Lageplan vorher studiert. Jetzt bin ich schon wieder der Neue.",src:"If only I had studied the campus map beforehand. Now I am the new guy again."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Universit\u00e4t",src:"the university",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Universit\u00e4ten.\nOften shortened to 'Uni' in spoken German.",example:"A: An welcher Universit\u00e4t studierst du?\nB: An der Freien Universit\u00e4t Berlin.\nA: Gef\u00e4llt dir die Uni?\nB: Ja, die Universit\u00e4t hat einen tollen Campus.",exampleSrc:"A: At which university do you study?\nB: At the Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin.\nA: Do you like the university?\nB: Yes, the university has a great campus.",funFact:"Germany has over 400 Hochschulen. The word traces to Latin 'universitas', a community of scholars. Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin was founded in 1948 as a 'free' alternative to Soviet-controlled Humboldt. The name itself is political history."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der H\u00f6rsaal",src:"the lecture hall",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. H\u00f6r (listen) + Saal (hall).\nPlural: die H\u00f6rs\u00e4le.",example:"A: Wo ist der H\u00f6rsaal 1A?\nB: Im Erdgeschoss, links um die Ecke.\nA: Wie gro\u00df ist der H\u00f6rsaal?\nB: Er hat 500 Pl\u00e4tze.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is lecture hall 1A?\nB: On the ground floor, left around the corner.\nA: How big is the lecture hall?\nB: It has 500 seats.",funFact:"'H\u00f6r' (hear/listen) + 'Saal' (hall). A 'listening hall.' German university H\u00f6rs\u00e4le can seat 500+ students. The word tells you your job: sit and listen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Mensa",src:"the university cafeteria",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Mensen.\nSubsidized student cafeteria.",example:"A: Gehen wir in die Mensa?\nB: Gerne! Was gibt es heute?\nA: Schnitzel mit Kartoffelsalat.\nB: Die Mensa ist der beste Ort am Campus.",exampleSrc:"A: Shall we go to the cafeteria?\nB: Sure! What is there today?\nA: Schnitzel with potato salad.\nB: The cafeteria is the best place on campus.",funFact:"A Mensa meal costs just 2-4 EUR for students, subsidized by the state. The Latin root 'mensa' means table. Everyone eats the same food at the same price. A democratic space."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Seminar",src:"the seminar",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. A small discussion class.\nContrast with Vorlesung (large lecture).",example:"A: Hast du heute ein Seminar?\nB: Ja, Linguistik-Seminar um 14 Uhr.\nA: Wie viele Leute sind im Seminar?\nB: Nur 25. Man muss aktiv mitmachen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a seminar today?\nB: Yes, linguistics seminar at 2 PM.\nA: How many people are in the seminar?\nB: Only 25. You have to actively participate.",funFact:"In German universities, a Seminar means an interactive class of 20-30 students. A Vorlesung has 200+ and expects listening. The Latin root 'seminarium' meant seed plot, where ideas grow."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Vorlesung",src:"the lecture",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Vor (before) + Lesung (reading).\n'Eine Vorlesung besuchen' (to attend a lecture).",example:"A: Wie war die Vorlesung?\nB: Interessant, aber sehr schnell.\nA: Konntest du alles mitschreiben?\nB: Nein, die Vorlesung war zu dicht.",exampleSrc:"A: How was the lecture?\nB: Interesting, but very fast.\nA: Could you write everything down?\nB: No, the lecture was too dense.",funFact:"'Vor' (before) + 'Lesung' (reading). A 'reading aloud.' Professors traditionally 'read' their material aloud. German students show appreciation by knocking on the desk, not clapping."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius hat seine erste Vorlesung. Was ist eine Vorlesung?",opts:["Ein kleines Seminar mit 20 Studenten","Ein praktisches Labor im Keller","Eine grosse Veranstaltung, bei der der Professor vortraegt","Eine muendliche Pruefung"],ans:"Eine grosse Veranstaltung, bei der der Professor vortraegt",hint:"A formal session where one speaker presents material to a large audience. Common in universities, not interactive."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Studiengang",src:"the degree program",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Studien (studies) + Gang (path).\n'Welchen Studiengang belegst du?'",example:"A: Welchen Studiengang hast du gew\u00e4hlt?\nB: Linguistik als Hauptfach.\nA: Ist der Studiengang schwer?\nB: Ja, aber sehr spannend.",exampleSrc:"A: Which degree program did you choose?\nB: Linguistics as a major.\nA: Is the degree program difficult?\nB: Yes, but very exciting.",funFact:"'Studien' (studies) + 'Gang' (path/course). Your path through academic study. German universities offer over 20,000 different Studieng\u00e4nge. The word captures it: a journey through knowledge."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Dozent",src:"the lecturer (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. N-Deklination: den Dozenten.\nBelow Professor, above Tutor.",example:"A: Wer h\u00e4lt die Vorlesung?\nB: Der Dozent, Herr Meier.\nA: Ist er streng?\nB: Nein, der Dozent erkl\u00e4rt alles sehr klar.",exampleSrc:"A: Who gives the lecture?\nB: The lecturer, Mr. Meier.\nA: Is he strict?\nB: No, the lecturer explains everything very clearly.",funFact:"Dozenten do the heavy lifting of German university teaching. They rank below Professor but above Tutor. The Latin root 'docens' simply means one who teaches."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Dozentin",src:"the lecturer (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Dozent + -in.\nGender-neutral alternative: Dozierende.",example:"A: Kennst du die Dozentin?\nB: Ja, Frau Dr. Schmidt. Sie ist sehr kompetent.\nA: Ist die Dozentin nett?\nB: Ja, aber anspruchsvoll.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know the lecturer?\nB: Yes, Dr. Schmidt. She is very competent.\nA: Is the lecturer nice?\nB: Yes, but demanding.",funFact:"Dozent + '-in.' The feminine form follows the standard pattern. German universities now use 'Dozierende' as a gender-neutral alternative, but Dozent/Dozentin remains standard in daily use."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fakult\u00e4t",src:"the faculty, the department",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Fakult\u00e4ten.\n'Die Philosophische Fakult\u00e4t.'",example:"A: Zu welcher Fakult\u00e4t geh\u00f6rst du?\nB: Zur Philosophischen Fakult\u00e4t.\nA: Wie viele Fakult\u00e4ten hat die Uni?\nB: Zw\u00f6lf. Jede Fakult\u00e4t ist wie eine kleine Uni.",exampleSrc:"A: Which faculty do you belong to?\nB: To the Faculty of Arts.\nA: How many faculties does the university have?\nB: Twelve. Each faculty is like a small university.",funFact:"Each Fakult\u00e4t is like a small university within the university. German universities have Philosophische, Naturwissenschaftliche, and Juristische Fakult\u00e4ten. The Latin root 'facultas' meant ability."},
{type:"mc",q:"In welcher Einrichtung essen Studierende fuer wenig Geld?",opts:["der Hoersaal","das Seminar","die Fakultaet","die Mensa"],ans:"die Mensa",hint:"A subsidized place on campus where students eat together. Meals cost 2-4 EUR."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l1b",title:"Herr Professor Doktor (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDFDB\uFE0F",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Herr Professor Doktor (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Einschreibung",src:"the enrollment, the registration",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Ein (in) + Schreibung (writing).\n'Die Einschreibung abschlie\u00dfen.'",example:"A: Hast du die Einschreibung schon gemacht?\nB: Ja, seit gestern bin ich eingeschrieben.\nA: Wann war die Frist f\u00fcr die Einschreibung?\nB: Bis zum 15. Oktober.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you done the enrollment yet?\nB: Yes, since yesterday I am enrolled.\nA: When was the deadline for enrollment?\nB: Until October 15th.",funFact:"You 'write yourself in' to the university. The Einschreibung deadline is sacred. Miss it and you wait a semester. A classic example of Nominalisierung: einschreiben becomes Einschreibung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Immatrikulation",src:"the formal enrollment",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Formal synonym of Einschreibung.\nMore bureaucratic register.",example:"A: Was ist der Unterschied zwischen Einschreibung und Immatrikulation?\nB: Es gibt keinen. Immatrikulation klingt nur formeller.\nA: Hast du deine Immatrikulationsbescheinigung?\nB: Ja, ich brauche sie f\u00fcr alles.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the difference between Einschreibung and Immatrikulation?\nB: There is none. Immatrikulation just sounds more formal.\nA: Do you have your enrollment certificate?\nB: Yes, I need it for everything.",funFact:"Your Immatrikulationsbescheinigung (enrollment certificate) is your student ID for everything. One of the longest compound words students encounter. Latin 'immatriculare' meant to enter someone in a register."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} ist eine Abteilung der Universitaet, zum Beispiel die Philosophische.",a:["Fakultaet"],opts:["Fakultaet","Mensa","Vorlesung","Einschreibung"],hint:"The organizational division of a university. From Latin 'facultas' (ability).",sSrc:"The faculty is a department of the university, for example the Faculty of Arts."},
{type:"teach",trg:"studieren",src:"to study (at university)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. NOT the same as 'lernen.'\n'Ich studiere Linguistik' = enrolled in a degree.",example:"A: Was studierst du?\nB: Ich studiere Linguistik.\nA: Seit wann studierst du?\nB: Seit diesem Semester. Ich studiere erst seit kurzem.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you study?\nB: I study linguistics.\nA: Since when have you been studying?\nB: Since this semester. I have only been studying for a short time.",funFact:"Did you know German has two words where English uses one? 'Studieren' means pursuing a degree (Latin 'studere', to be eager). 'Lernen' means learning a skill. 'Ich studiere Linguistik' vs. 'Ich lerne Deutsch.' Two different activities."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wann muss man die Einschreibung abschliessen?",opts:["Vor der festgelegten Frist","Nach dem ersten Semester","Nach der ersten Vorlesung","Waehrend der Semesterferien"],ans:"Vor der festgelegten Frist",hint:"Enrollment has a strict deadline. Missing it means waiting another semester."},
{type:"teach",trg:"immatrikulieren",src:"to formally enroll",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular, reflexive: sich immatrikulieren.\nThe bureaucratic verb for becoming a student.",example:"A: Hast du dich schon immatrikuliert?\nB: Ja, ich habe mich letzte Woche immatrikuliert.\nA: Wie war der Prozess?\nB: Viel Papierkram. Typisch deutsch.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you enrolled yet?\nB: Yes, I enrolled last week.\nA: How was the process?\nB: A lot of paperwork. Typically German.",funFact:"See Immatrikulation. Reflexive: 'sich immatrikulieren.' You immatrikulieren yourself. Once done, you get your Studentenausweis. The bureaucratic verb for becoming an official student."},
{type:"teach",trg:"akademisch",src:"academic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Akademisches Viertel' = lectures\nstart 15 minutes late (written 'c.t.').",example:"A: Was bedeutet 'akademisches Viertel'?\nB: Die Vorlesung f\u00e4ngt 15 Minuten sp\u00e4ter an.\nA: Das ist eine akademische Tradition?\nB: Ja, seit Jahrhunderten!",exampleSrc:"A: What does 'academic quarter' mean?\nB: The lecture starts 15 minutes later.\nA: That is an academic tradition?\nB: Yes, for centuries!",funFact:"From Greek 'akademeia' (Plato's school). 'Akademisches Viertel' means lectures start 15 minutes late. Written 'c.t.' (cum tempore). If a lecture is at 10:00 c.t., it starts at 10:15. This is tradition, not laziness."},
{type:"teach",trg:"wissenschaftlich",src:"scientific, scholarly",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. Wissenschaft (scholarship) + -lich.\nCovers ALL scholarship, not just natural science.",example:"A: Ist deine Arbeit wissenschaftlich?\nB: Ja, sie folgt wissenschaftlichen Methoden.\nA: Was bedeutet wissenschaftliches Arbeiten?\nB: Quellen, Struktur, objektive Analyse.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your work scholarly?\nB: Yes, it follows scholarly methods.\nA: What does academic writing mean?\nB: Sources, structure, objective analysis.",funFact:"'Wissenschaft' (science/scholarship) + '-lich.' 'Wissenschaftliches Arbeiten' is a course every German student must take. The word covers ALL scholarship, not just natural science."},
{type:"teach",trg:"grundlegend",src:"fundamental, foundational",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. Grund (ground) + legend (laying).\n'Grundlegende Kenntnisse' (fundamental knowledge).",example:"A: Sind die ersten Vorlesungen grundlegend?\nB: Ja, sie legen die Grundlagen.\nA: Was ist grundlegend f\u00fcr Linguistik?\nB: Phonetik, Syntax und Semantik sind grundlegend.",exampleSrc:"A: Are the first lectures fundamental?\nB: Yes, they lay the foundations.\nA: What is fundamental for linguistics?\nB: Phonetics, syntax, and semantics are fundamental.",funFact:"'Grund' (ground/foundation) + 'legend' (laying). The word paints a picture: laying the foundation. 'Grundlegende Kenntnisse' is used constantly in academic writing. You cannot skip the grundlegenden concepts."},
{type:"fb",s:"An der Universitaet {1} man ein Fach wie Linguistik oder Medizin.",a:["studiert"],opts:["studiert","lernt","forscht","immatrikuliert"],hint:"The specific verb for being enrolled in a university degree program. Not the same as 'lernen'.",sSrc:"At the university, one studies a subject like linguistics or medicine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"insbesondere",src:"in particular, especially",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Adverb. In + s + besondere.\nFormal register. 'Insbesondere in der Linguistik.'",example:"A: Was interessiert dich an der Uni?\nB: Die Sprachwissenschaft, insbesondere die Phonetik.\nA: Warum insbesondere Phonetik?\nB: Weil Kl\u00e4nge mich faszinieren.",exampleSrc:"A: What interests you about university?\nB: Linguistics, in particular phonetics.\nA: Why phonetics in particular?\nB: Because sounds fascinate me.",funFact:"'In' + 's' + 'besondere.' A formal adverb beloved by German academics. One word where English needs two. Elegant and precise. You will hear it in every lecture and read it in every paper."},
{type:"teach",trg:"grunds\u00e4tzlich",src:"in principle, fundamentally",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Adverb. Grundsatz (principle) + -lich.\n'Grunds\u00e4tzlich gilt...' (In principle, ... applies).",example:"A: Kann man den Studiengang wechseln?\nB: Grunds\u00e4tzlich ja, aber es gibt Fristen.\nA: Also grunds\u00e4tzlich m\u00f6glich?\nB: Ja, grunds\u00e4tzlich schon.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you change your degree program?\nB: In principle yes, but there are deadlines.\nA: So fundamentally possible?\nB: Yes, fundamentally speaking.",funFact:"'Grundsatz' (principle) + '-lich.' A hedging word: it says 'in theory' while leaving room for exceptions. 'Grunds\u00e4tzlich gilt...' opens many an academic argument."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anhand",src:"by means of, on the basis of",pos:"prep",gender:null,note:"Preposition + Genitiv. An (at) + Hand (hand).\n'Anhand der Daten' (on the basis of the data).",example:"A: Wie beweist man eine These?\nB: Anhand von Daten und Quellen.\nA: Anhand welcher Methode?\nB: Anhand der empirischen Forschung.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you prove a thesis?\nB: By means of data and sources.\nA: By means of which method?\nB: By means of empirical research.",funFact:"'An' (at) + 'Hand' (hand). Literally 'at the hand of.' Academic German uses this constantly. Always followed by Genitiv. You will see 'anhand' on every page of every German research paper."},
{type:"teach",trg:"hinsichtlich",src:"with regard to, concerning",pos:"prep",gender:null,note:"Preposition + Genitiv. Hin (toward) + Sicht (view).\nFormal academic register.",example:"A: Was sagt der Professor hinsichtlich der Klausur?\nB: Hinsichtlich der Klausur gibt es neue Regeln.\nA: Hinsichtlich des Termins?\nB: Der Termin bleibt hinsichtlich des Plans gleich.",exampleSrc:"A: What does the professor say with regard to the exam?\nB: With regard to the exam there are new rules.\nA: Regarding the date?\nB: The date remains the same according to the plan.",funFact:"'Hin' (toward) + 'Sicht' (view) + '-lich.' A formal preposition with Genitiv. One of the hallmarks of academic register. You will almost never hear it in casual conversation."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Vorlesung",src:"lecture"},{trg:"Seminar",src:"discussion class"},{trg:"Mensa",src:"cafeteria"},{trg:"Fakult\u00e4t",src:"faculty/department"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"wry",art:"de-fub-dahlem-building",trg:"Verumius findet den H\u00f6rsaal. Zehn Minuten zu sp\u00e4t, aber niemand schaut auf. Akademisches Viertel. Er setzt sich in die letzte Reihe und atmet aus. Die Universit\u00e4t hat ihn noch nicht ausgespuckt. Tag eins, Punkt eins: \u00fcberlebt.",src:"Verumius finds the lecture hall. Ten minutes late, but nobody looks up. Academic quarter. He sits in the last row and exhales. The university has not spit him out yet. Day one, item one: survived."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Immatrikulation'?",opts:["with regard to, concerning","by means of, on the basis of","to study (at university)","the formal enrollment"],ans:"the formal enrollment",hint:"Latin: in + matricula (register). Official university registration."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to formally enroll' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["immatrikulieren"],opts:["die Immatrikulation","immatrikulieren","die Fakult\\u00e4t","die Einschreibung"],hint:"The verb form of Immatrikulation. To officially enroll at a university.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to formally enroll' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'insbesondere'?",opts:["in particular, especially","the university","the lecturer (female)","in principle, fundamentally"],ans:"in particular, especially",hint:"Ins (into the) + besondere (special). Singling out one specific thing."},
{type:"fb",s:"{1} von Daten und Quellen.",a:["anhand"],opts:["immatrikulieren","anhand","studieren","grunds\\u00e4tzlich"],hint:"An (at) + Hand (hand). Literally 'at hand.' Using evidence or examples.",sSrc:"By means of data and sources."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'hinsichtlich'?",opts:["the lecturer (male)","with regard to, concerning","the faculty, the department","by means of, on the basis of"],ans:"with regard to, concerning",hint:"Hin (toward) + Sicht (view) + -lich. Looking toward a specific aspect."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l2",title:"Die Sprache der Wissenschaft",icon:"\uD83D\uDD2C",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Sprache der Wissenschaft",desc:"The language of research. Learn the key words for academic work. Recognize the pattern between verbs and their nominalized forms.",goals:["Learn 20 words from the language of research","Recognize the pattern of Nominalisierung (verb to noun)","Build your academic German toolkit"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Forschung",src:"the research",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'forschen' (to research).\n'Forschung und Lehre' (research and teaching).",example:"A: Was ist das Ziel deiner Forschung?\nB: Ich untersuche Sprachmuster.\nA: Ist Forschung schwer?\nB: Ja, aber die Forschung macht Spa\u00df.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the goal of your research?\nB: I investigate language patterns.\nA: Is research hard?\nB: Yes, but the research is fun.",funFact:"From 'forschen' (to research). 'Forschung und Lehre' (research and teaching) is the dual mission of every German university. The Forschung half is what makes a university different from a school."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Hypothese",src:"the hypothesis",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Hypothesen.\n'Eine Hypothese aufstellen' (to put forward a hypothesis).",example:"A: Hast du schon eine Hypothese?\nB: Ja, meine Hypothese ist, dass Nominalisierung Texte schwerer macht.\nA: Interessante Hypothese.\nB: Ich muss sie noch testen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a hypothesis yet?\nB: Yes, my hypothesis is that nominalization makes texts harder.\nA: Interesting hypothesis.\nB: I still need to test it.",funFact:"From Greek 'hypothesis' (foundation). German academic writing demands that you state your Hypothese clearly before investigating it. 'Eine Hypothese aufstellen' is the first step of every research project."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Methode",src:"the method",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Methoden.\n'Wissenschaftliche Methoden' (scientific methods).",example:"A: Welche Methode verwendest du?\nB: Eine quantitative Methode mit Statistik.\nA: Ist die Methode zuverl\u00e4ssig?\nB: Ja, die Methode wurde schon oft getestet.",exampleSrc:"A: Which method are you using?\nB: A quantitative method with statistics.\nA: Is the method reliable?\nB: Yes, the method has been tested many times.",funFact:"From Greek 'methodos' (pursuit of knowledge). 'Wissenschaftliche Methoden' is the backbone of German research. Every Hausarbeit must describe its Methode explicitly. No method, no scholarship."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Statistik",src:"the statistics",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. 'Laut Statistik' (according to statistics).\nOriginally meant data about the state.",example:"A: Brauchst du Statistik f\u00fcr dein Studium?\nB: Ja, die Statistik ist Pflicht.\nA: Magst du Statistik?\nB: Laut Statistik m\u00f6gen 50% der Studenten sie nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you need statistics for your studies?\nB: Yes, statistics is mandatory.\nA: Do you like statistics?\nB: According to statistics, 50% of students do not like it.",funFact:"'Laut Statistik...' (according to statistics) starts many a German argument. The word originally meant 'data about the state,' from Latin 'statisticum.' Now it covers all quantitative analysis."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Studie",src:"the study (research)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Studien.\nNot the same as 'Studium' (university studies).",example:"A: Kennst du die neue Studie?\nB: Welche Studie meinst du?\nA: Die Studie \u00fcber Sprachlernen.\nB: Ja, eine sehr interessante Studie.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know the new study?\nB: Which study do you mean?\nA: The study about language learning.\nB: Yes, a very interesting study.",funFact:"Watch out: a Studie is a specific research project, not your university studies (that is Studium). Latin 'studium' is the root. 'Eine Studie durchführen' (to conduct a study) produces Ergebnisse."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Wissenschaftlerin stellt eine {1} auf und testet sie mit Daten.",a:["Hypothese"],opts:["Hypothese","Methode","Statistik","Forschung"],hint:"From Greek 'hypothesis.' The assumption you test at the start of every research project.",sSrc:"The scientist puts forward a hypothesis and tests it with data."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Analyse",src:"the analysis",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Analysen.\n'Eine gr\u00fcndliche Analyse' (a thorough analysis).",example:"A: Wie l\u00e4uft die Analyse?\nB: Die Analyse der Daten ist fast fertig.\nA: Zeigt die Analyse etwas Neues?\nB: Ja, die Analyse best\u00e4tigt unsere Hypothese.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the analysis going?\nB: The analysis of the data is almost done.\nA: Does the analysis show something new?\nB: Yes, the analysis confirms our hypothesis.",funFact:"From Greek 'analysis' (breaking up). Academic German loves this word. The verb form 'analysieren' is equally common. Analyse (noun) and analysieren (verb) are a Nominalisierung pair."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Ergebnis",src:"the result, the outcome",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: die Ergebnisse.\n'Die Ergebnisse zeigen...' (The results show...).",example:"A: Was zeigen die Ergebnisse?\nB: Die Ergebnisse sind \u00fcberraschend.\nA: Positiv \u00fcberraschend?\nB: Ja, das Ergebnis \u00fcbertrifft unsere Erwartungen.",exampleSrc:"A: What do the results show?\nB: The results are surprising.\nA: Positively surprising?\nB: Yes, the result exceeds our expectations.",funFact:"From 'ergeben' (to result in). 'Die Ergebnisse zeigen...' opens paragraphs in every German research paper. Neuter because of the Er- prefix pattern. Plural: Ergebnisse."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Untersuchung",src:"the investigation, the examination",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'untersuchen' (to investigate).\nClassic Nominalisierung: verb + -ung.",example:"A: Was ist das Thema deiner Untersuchung?\nB: Die Untersuchung befasst sich mit Sprachmustern.\nA: Wie lange dauert die Untersuchung?\nB: Die Untersuchung l\u00e4uft noch drei Monate.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the topic of your investigation?\nB: The investigation deals with language patterns.\nA: How long does the investigation take?\nB: The investigation runs for another three months.",funFact:"From 'untersuchen' (to investigate). Notice the pattern: the verb 'untersuchen' becomes the noun 'Untersuchung' with the -ung suffix. This is Nominalisierung. Academic German loves this transformation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Quelle",src:"the source",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Quellen.\nLiterally 'spring' (as in water).",example:"A: Wie viele Quellen hast du?\nB: \u00dcber zwanzig Quellen.\nA: Sind die Quellen zuverl\u00e4ssig?\nB: Ja, nur akademische Quellen.",exampleSrc:"A: How many sources do you have?\nB: Over twenty sources.\nA: Are the sources reliable?\nB: Yes, only academic sources.",funFact:"Literally 'spring/source' (as in water). Knowledge flows from its source. 'Quellenangabe' (source citation) is mandatory in German academia. Forgetting your Quellen is academic suicide."},
{type:"fb",s:"Bevor man Daten sammelt, braucht man eine klare {1}.",a:["Methode"],opts:["Statistik","Methode","Studie","Quelle"],hint:"The systematic approach to research. From Greek 'methodos' (pursuit of knowledge).",sSrc:"Before collecting data, you need a clear method."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die These",src:"the thesis, the proposition",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Plural: die Thesen.\n'Eine These verteidigen' (to defend a thesis).",example:"A: Was ist deine These?\nB: Meine These: Nominalisierung macht Texte formeller.\nA: Kannst du die These belegen?\nB: Ja, anhand der Daten.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your thesis?\nB: My thesis: nominalization makes texts more formal.\nA: Can you support the thesis?\nB: Yes, on the basis of the data.",funFact:"From Greek 'thesis' (placement). Martin Luther nailed 95 Thesen to a church door. The word carries weight in German. 'Eine These verteidigen' is what every student must do."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was zeigen die Ergebnisse einer Studie?",opts:["Die Forschungsfrage","Die Methode des Forschers","Das Ergebnis der Untersuchung","Die Hypothese des Autors"],ans:"Das Ergebnis der Untersuchung",hint:"The word for what research produces. Neuter noun from the verb 'ergeben' (to result in)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"analysieren",src:"to analyze",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From Analyse.\n'Daten analysieren' (to analyze data).",example:"A: Hast du die Daten schon analysiert?\nB: Ja, ich analysiere gerade die letzten Ergebnisse.\nA: Was hast du analysiert?\nB: Textmuster in akademischen Arbeiten.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you analyzed the data yet?\nB: Yes, I am currently analyzing the last results.\nA: What did you analyze?\nB: Text patterns in academic papers.",funFact:"From Analyse. Notice: Analyse (noun) and analysieren (verb) are a pair. The noun came first from Greek; the verb was formed from it. This reverse process is called Verbalisierung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"untersuchen",src:"to investigate, to examine",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Unter (under) + suchen (search).\n'Wir untersuchen den Zusammenhang.'",example:"A: Was untersuchst du?\nB: Ich untersuche den Zusammenhang zwischen Sprache und Denken.\nA: Wie untersuchst du das?\nB: Mit Interviews und Textanalysen.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you investigating?\nB: I am investigating the connection between language and thought.\nA: How are you investigating that?\nB: With interviews and text analyses.",funFact:"'Unter' (under) + 'suchen' (to search). Searching underneath the surface. The noun: Untersuchung (investigation). A classic Nominalisierung pair: untersuchen becomes die Untersuchung."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} 'Die Daten zeigen...' kommt in jeder wissenschaftlichen Arbeit vor.",a:["Analyse"],opts:["These","Quelle","Statistik","Analyse"],hint:"The systematic examination of data. From Greek 'analysis' (breaking up).",sSrc:"The analysis 'The data show...' appears in every academic paper."},
{type:"teach",trg:"definieren",src:"to define",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From Latin 'definire.'\n'Den Begriff definieren' (to define the term).",example:"A: Wie definierst du 'Nominalisierung'?\nB: Ich definiere es als die Umwandlung von Verben zu Nomen.\nA: Gut definiert!\nB: Man muss Begriffe klar definieren.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you define 'nominalization'?\nB: I define it as the transformation of verbs into nouns.\nA: Well defined!\nB: You must define terms clearly.",funFact:"Rule number one in German academic writing: define before you argue. Every Hausarbeit begins by defining its key terms. The Latin root 'definire' literally meant 'to set boundaries.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"formulieren",src:"to formulate, to phrase",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From Latin 'formulare.'\n'Eine Hypothese formulieren.'",example:"A: Wie w\u00fcrdest du das formulieren?\nB: Ich w\u00fcrde es so formulieren: Die Daten zeigen...\nA: Gut formuliert.\nB: Man muss pr\u00e4zise formulieren.",exampleSrc:"A: How would you phrase that?\nB: I would phrase it like this: The data show...\nA: Well phrased.\nB: You must formulate precisely.",funFact:"'Wie würden Sie das formulieren?' is what advisors ask students constantly. Precision in phrasing is everything in German academia. The Latin root 'formulare' hints at fitting thought into form."},
{type:"teach",trg:"interpretieren",src:"to interpret",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From Latin 'interpretari.'\n'Ergebnisse interpretieren' (to interpret results).",example:"A: Wie interpretierst du die Ergebnisse?\nB: Ich interpretiere sie positiv.\nA: Kann man sie auch anders interpretieren?\nB: Ja, man muss verschiedene M\u00f6glichkeiten interpretieren.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you interpret the results?\nB: I interpret them positively.\nA: Can one interpret them differently?\nB: Yes, one must interpret various possibilities.",funFact:"Data alone says nothing. The Interpretation is where academic skill shows. 'Wie interpretieren Sie diese Daten?' separates good researchers from great ones. Latin root: 'interpretari.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"vergleichen",src:"to compare",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Strong verb: verglich, verglichen. Inseparable.\n'Zwei Studien vergleichen.'",example:"A: Hast du die beiden Studien verglichen?\nB: Ja, ich habe sie sorgf\u00e4ltig verglichen.\nA: Und der Vergleich?\nB: Die Ergebnisse sind \u00e4hnlich.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you compared the two studies?\nB: Yes, I compared them carefully.\nA: And the comparison?\nB: The results are similar.",funFact:"'Ver-' + 'gleichen' (to equal/level). You make things 'equal' to see the differences. Strong verb: vergleichen/verglich/verglichen. Der Vergleich is the nominalized form."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Verb bedeutet, einen Begriff genau zu bestimmen?",opts:["definieren","vergleichen","formulieren","interpretieren"],ans:"definieren",hint:"From Latin 'definire' (to set boundaries). Every academic paper starts by doing this to its key terms."},
{type:"teach",trg:"empirisch",src:"empirical, based on observation",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. The opposite of 'theoretisch.'\n'Empirische Forschung' (empirical research).",example:"A: Ist deine Forschung empirisch?\nB: Ja, rein empirisch. Alles basiert auf Daten.\nA: Nicht theoretisch?\nB: Nein, empirisch. Beobachtung vor Theorie.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your research empirical?\nB: Yes, purely empirical. Everything is based on data.\nA: Not theoretical?\nB: No, empirical. Observation before theory.",funFact:"From Greek 'empeiria' (experience). Research based on data, not just theory. The opposite of 'theoretisch.' A key academic distinction in every German research seminar."},
{type:"teach",trg:"theoretisch",src:"theoretical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Greek 'theoria' (contemplation).\n'Theoretisch m\u00f6glich' (theoretically possible).",example:"A: Ist das theoretisch m\u00f6glich?\nB: Theoretisch ja, praktisch schwierig.\nA: Brauchst du einen theoretischen Rahmen?\nB: Ja, jede Arbeit braucht einen theoretischen Rahmen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that theoretically possible?\nB: Theoretically yes, practically difficult.\nA: Do you need a theoretical framework?\nB: Yes, every paper needs a theoretical framework.",funFact:"From Greek 'theoria' (contemplation). 'Theoretisch m\u00f6glich' always implies 'but practically unlikely.' Academic work needs both: theoretischer Rahmen (theoretical framework) + empirische Daten."},
{type:"teach",trg:"systematisch",src:"systematic",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Greek 'systema.'\n'Systematische Untersuchung.'",example:"A: Gehst du systematisch vor?\nB: Ja, immer systematisch. Schritt f\u00fcr Schritt.\nA: Warum ist systematisch wichtig?\nB: Ohne systematisches Vorgehen keine Wissenschaft.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you proceeding systematically?\nB: Yes, always systematically. Step by step.\nA: Why is systematic important?\nB: Without a systematic approach, no scholarship.",funFact:"From Greek 'systema.' German scholarship values system above all. A systematischer Ansatz (systematic approach) is not optional; it is expected. Unsystematisch is an insult in academia."},
{type:"teach",trg:"objektiv",src:"objective",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. The opposite of 'subjektiv.'\n'Bleiben Sie objektiv' (Stay objective).",example:"A: Ist deine Analyse objektiv?\nB: Ich versuche, objektiv zu bleiben.\nA: Das ist schwer.\nB: Ja, aber objektiv zu sein ist das Ziel.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your analysis objective?\nB: I try to stay objective.\nA: That is hard.\nB: Yes, but being objective is the goal.",funFact:"'Bleiben Sie objektiv' is every German professor's mantra. Your personal opinion stays out of the paper. The word traces to Latin 'objectivus,' and 'objektive Analyse' is what every paper must deliver."},
{type:"fb",s:"Gute Forschung muss {1} sein, also auf Beobachtungen basieren.",a:["empirisch"],opts:["theoretisch","empirisch","systematisch","objektiv"],hint:"Based on observation and data, not just theory. From Greek 'empeiria' (experience).",sSrc:"Good research must be empirical, meaning based on observations."},
{type:"tip",title:"Nominalisierung: Die deutsche Superkraft",text:"German constantly turns verbs and adjectives into nouns. The pattern:\n\nVerb + -ung = feminine noun:\nuntersuchen > die Untersuchung\nentwickeln > die Entwicklung\nforschen > die Forschung\n\nThis is Nominalisierung. Academic German LOVES it.\n\nA single noun can replace an entire clause:\n'Die Untersuchung der Daten' = 'dass man die Daten untersucht.'\n\nNominalisierung makes academic writing denser and more formal.",deepDive:{title:"Why Nominalisierung?",text:"Nominalisierung is the tool of academic compression. Instead of 'Wir haben untersucht, wie...' you write 'Die Untersuchung zeigt...' The sentence becomes shorter, more impersonal, and more formal. That is the academic style. Spoken German prefers the verbal style. Written German prefers the nominal style. Both are correct, but context determines the choice."}},
{type:"teach",trg:"forschen",src:"to do research, to investigate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From 'Forschung' (research).\nThe verb behind every scientific inquiry.",example:"A: Forschst du gerade an einem Thema?\nB: Ja, ich forsche über Sprachveraenderungen.\nA: Wie lange forscht man für eine Hausarbeit?\nB: Mindestens zwei bis drei Wochen.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you currently researching a topic?\nB: Yes, I research language change.\nA: How long does one research for a term paper?\nB: At least two to three weeks.",funFact:"'Forschung' (research) is the nominalized form. Germany invests heavily in Forschung und Entwicklung (research and development). 'Der Forscher' and 'die Forscherin' are the agent nouns. Renowned for Grundlagenforschung (basic research)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Bevor man forscht, muss man eine {1} aufstellen.",a:["Hypothese"],opts:["Statistik","Quelle","Mensa","Hypothese"],hint:"An informed guess about what research will reveal. Of Greek origin.",sSrc:"Before doing research, you must put forward a hypothesis."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"analysieren",src:"die Analyse"},{trg:"untersuchen",src:"die Untersuchung"},{trg:"forschen",src:"die Forschung"},{trg:"definieren",src:"die Definition"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Welcher Ausdruck geh\u00f6rt in eine wissenschaftliche Arbeit?",opts:["Die empirische Untersuchung zeigt...","Ich finde das cool.","Das ist irgendwie interessant.","Meiner Meinung nach ist das so gemeint."],ans:"Die empirische Untersuchung zeigt...",hint:"Academic German uses nominalized forms, precise adjectives, and avoids personal opinion markers."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l3",title:"Die erste Vorlesung",icon:"\uD83C\uDF93",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die erste Vorlesung",desc:"Survive your first German lecture. Learn vocabulary for argumentation and logical thinking. Master the Konjunktiv II past for hypothetical past events.",goals:["Learn 20 words for argumentation and conclusions","Master the Konjunktiv II past (hätte/wäre + Partizip II)","Follow an academic lecture in German"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"intense",art:"de-fub-hoersaal",trg:"H\u00f6rsaal 1A. Zweihundert Studenten. Der Professor spricht frei, ohne Notizen, und l\u00e4uft \u00fcber die B\u00fchne. Folien dicht mit Text. Verumius schreibt so schnell er kann. Jedes dritte Wort ist neu.",src:"Lecture hall 1A. Two hundred students. The professor speaks freely, without notes, pacing the stage. Slides dense with text. Verumius writes as fast as he can. Every third word is new."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"reflective",art:"de-fub-hoersaal",trg:"Der Professor sagt: 'H\u00e4tte man diesen Zusammenhang fr\u00fcher erkannt, w\u00e4re die Entwicklung anders verlaufen.' Verumius h\u00e4lt inne. Vergangenheit, aber hypothetisch. Eine neue Grammatik.",src:"The professor says: 'Had they recognized this connection earlier, the development would have gone differently.' Verumius pauses. Past tense, but hypothetical. A new grammar."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"thinking",art:"de-fub-hoersaal",trg:"H\u00e4tte ich doch vorher den Text gelesen. Dann h\u00e4tte ich mehr verstanden. Aber so lerne ich: unter Druck.",src:"If only I had read the text beforehand. Then I would have understood more. But this is how I learn: under pressure."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Zusammenhang",src:"the connection, the context",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Zusammen (together) + Hang (slope).\n'In diesem Zusammenhang' (in this context).",example:"A: In welchem Zusammenhang steht das?\nB: Im Zusammenhang mit der Forschungsfrage.\nA: Siehst du den Zusammenhang?\nB: Ja, der Zusammenhang wird jetzt klar.",exampleSrc:"A: In what context does this stand?\nB: In the context of the research question.\nA: Do you see the connection?\nB: Yes, the connection is becoming clear now.",funFact:"'Zusammen' (together) + 'Hang' (hang/slope). Things that 'hang together.' 'In diesem Zusammenhang' opens paragraphs in every academic paper. Plural: Zusammenh\u00e4nge."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Bedeutung",src:"the meaning, the significance",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'bedeuten' (to mean).\n'Von gro\u00dfer Bedeutung' (of great significance).",example:"A: Was ist die Bedeutung dieses Begriffs?\nB: Die Bedeutung ist 'Zusammenhang.'\nA: Hat das eine tiefere Bedeutung?\nB: Ja, die Bedeutung geht \u00fcber das W\u00f6rterbuch hinaus.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the meaning of this term?\nB: The meaning is 'connection.'\nA: Does it have a deeper significance?\nB: Yes, the significance goes beyond the dictionary.",funFact:"From 'bedeuten' (to mean). Academic German distinguishes between Bedeutung (meaning) and Wichtigkeit (importance). Bedeutung is deeper. 'Von gro\u00dfer Bedeutung' signals that something truly matters."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Entwicklung",src:"the development",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Ent- (un-) + Wicklung (winding).\nLiterally 'unwinding,' something that unfolds.",example:"A: Wie war die Entwicklung im letzten Jahr?\nB: Die Entwicklung war sehr positiv.\nA: Welche Entwicklung erwartest du?\nB: Eine stetige Entwicklung nach oben.",exampleSrc:"A: How was the development last year?\nB: The development was very positive.\nA: What development do you expect?\nB: A steady upward development.",funFact:"'Ent-' (un-) + 'Wicklung' (winding). Literally 'unwinding.' Something that unfolds over time. 'Die historische Entwicklung' frames every academic narrative. Nominalisierung from 'entwickeln.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Darstellung",src:"the presentation, the depiction",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Dar (there) + Stellung (placement).\n'Die Darstellung der Ergebnisse.'",example:"A: Wie ist die Darstellung der Ergebnisse?\nB: Die Darstellung ist klar und \u00fcbersichtlich.\nA: Eine gute Darstellung ist wichtig.\nB: Ja, die Darstellung entscheidet \u00fcber den Erfolg.",exampleSrc:"A: How is the presentation of the results?\nB: The presentation is clear and well-organized.\nA: A good presentation is important.\nB: Yes, the presentation determines the success.",funFact:"'Dar' (there) + 'Stellung' (placement). You 'place something there' for others to see. Academic writing IS Darstellung: presenting your findings for the world."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Schlussfolgerung",src:"the conclusion, the inference",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Schluss + Folgerung.\nTriple compound: Schluss + Folge + -ung.",example:"A: Was ist deine Schlussfolgerung?\nB: Meine Schlussfolgerung: Nominalisierung ist produktiv.\nA: Eine logische Schlussfolgerung.\nB: Ja, die Schlussfolgerung basiert auf Daten.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your conclusion?\nB: My conclusion: nominalization is productive.\nA: A logical conclusion.\nB: Yes, the conclusion is based on data.",funFact:"'Schluss' (conclusion) + 'Folgerung' (inference). Triple compound. 'Welche Schlussfolgerung ziehen Sie?' (What conclusion do you draw?). The crown of academic argument."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist die Bedeutung des Wortes 'Zusammenhang'?",opts:["Trennung oder Spaltung","Verbindung, Kontext","Darstellung oder Erlaeuterung","Verschlechterung"],ans:"Verbindung, Kontext",hint:"Things that 'hang together'. Used constantly in academic writing with 'in diesem...'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Grundlage",src:"the foundation, the basis",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Grund (ground) + Lage (position).\n'Auf der Grundlage von Daten.'",example:"A: Was ist die Grundlage deiner Arbeit?\nB: Empirische Daten bilden die Grundlage.\nA: Ist die Grundlage stabil?\nB: Ja, eine solide Grundlage.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the foundation of your work?\nB: Empirical data form the foundation.\nA: Is the foundation stable?\nB: Yes, a solid foundation.",funFact:"'Grund' (ground) + 'Lage' (position/layer). The bedrock on which your argument stands. 'Auf der Grundlage von Daten' appears in every serious German research paper."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Sachverhalt",src:"the state of affairs, the facts",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Sach (matter) + Verhalt (condition).\n'Den Sachverhalt darstellen.'",example:"A: Kannst du den Sachverhalt erkl\u00e4ren?\nB: Der Sachverhalt ist komplex.\nA: Stelle den Sachverhalt einfach dar.\nB: Der Sachverhalt: Sprache ver\u00e4ndert sich st\u00e4ndig.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you explain the state of affairs?\nB: The state of affairs is complex.\nA: Present the facts simply.\nB: The facts: language constantly changes.",funFact:"'Sach' (thing/matter) + 'Verhalt' (condition). Pure academic German. No emotional coloring, just the facts. 'Den Sachverhalt darstellen' means to present the facts objectively."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} ist das logische Ergebnis einer Argumentation.",a:["Schlussfolgerung"],opts:["Schlussfolgerung","Grundlage","Entwicklung","Veraenderung"],hint:"A triple compound noun: conclusion + inference + nominalization suffix. The crown of an academic argument.",sSrc:"The conclusion is the logical result of an argumentation."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Ver\u00e4nderung",src:"the change, the transformation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Ver- + \u00c4nderung (change).\nStronger than '\u00c4nderung' alone.",example:"A: Siehst du eine Ver\u00e4nderung?\nB: Ja, eine grundlegende Ver\u00e4nderung.\nA: Seit wann gibt es diese Ver\u00e4nderung?\nB: Die Ver\u00e4nderung begann vor zehn Jahren.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you see a change?\nB: Yes, a fundamental change.\nA: Since when has this change existed?\nB: The change began ten years ago.",funFact:"'Ver-' + '\u00c4nderung' (change). The ver- prefix implies thoroughness. 'Grundlegende Ver\u00e4nderungen' (fundamental changes). More complete than a simple \u00c4nderung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"begr\u00fcnden",src:"to justify, to give reasons",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Be- + gr\u00fcnden (to found).\n'Begr\u00fcnden Sie Ihre These.'",example:"A: Kannst du deine Meinung begr\u00fcnden?\nB: Ja, ich begr\u00fcnde sie anhand der Daten.\nA: Gut begr\u00fcndet!\nB: Man muss alles begr\u00fcnden k\u00f6nnen.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you justify your opinion?\nB: Yes, I justify it on the basis of the data.\nA: Well justified!\nB: You must be able to justify everything.",funFact:"'Be-' + 'gr\u00fcnden' (to found). Every claim in German academia must be begr\u00fcndet (justified). No argument without Begr\u00fcndung. The noun is die Begr\u00fcndung."},
{type:"teach",trg:"argumentieren",src:"to argue (academically)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. Not fighting, but building\na logical case. '\u00dcberzeugend argumentieren.'",example:"A: Wie argumentiert der Autor?\nB: Er argumentiert logisch und sachlich.\nA: \u00dcberzeugend argumentiert?\nB: Ja, die Argumentation ist stichhaltig.",exampleSrc:"A: How does the author argue?\nB: He argues logically and factually.\nA: Convincingly argued?\nB: Yes, the argumentation is sound.",funFact:"In German academia, argumentieren means building a logical case, not fighting. 'Wie argumentiert der Autor?' is a standard exam question. Latin root: 'argumentari.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'begruenden' im akademischen Kontext?",opts:["bloss etwas wiederholen","etwas mit Gruenden belegen","stark vereinfachen","kuerzer zusammenfassen"],ans:"etwas mit Gruenden belegen",hint:"To provide reasons for a claim. Every statement in academia must be supported this way."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l3b",title:"Die erste Vorlesung (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83C\uDF93",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die erste Vorlesung (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"er\u00f6rtern",src:"to discuss, to examine thoroughly",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Formal academic register.\n'Ein Thema er\u00f6rtern.'",example:"A: K\u00f6nnen wir das Thema er\u00f6rtern?\nB: Ja, lassen Sie uns das gr\u00fcndlich er\u00f6rtern.\nA: Wie er\u00f6rtert man ein Thema?\nB: Systematisch und mit Belegen.",exampleSrc:"A: Can we discuss the topic?\nB: Yes, let us examine it thoroughly.\nA: How does one discuss a topic?\nB: Systematically and with evidence.",funFact:"Old German 'ert\u00f6rtern' (to explore a place). The Er\u00f6rterung (discussion essay) is a standard German school format. Every student writes hundreds. Formal register only."},
{type:"teach",trg:"folgern",src:"to conclude, to infer",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From 'Folge' (consequence).\n'Daraus l\u00e4sst sich folgern, dass...'",example:"A: Was folgerst du daraus?\nB: Ich folgere, dass die Hypothese stimmt.\nA: Kann man das sicher folgern?\nB: Ja, daraus l\u00e4sst sich folgern, dass...",exampleSrc:"A: What do you conclude from that?\nB: I conclude that the hypothesis is correct.\nA: Can one conclude that with certainty?\nB: Yes, from this one can conclude that...",funFact:"From 'Folge' (consequence). The academic verb for drawing a conclusion. 'Daraus l\u00e4sst sich folgern, dass...' (From this one can conclude that...). Related to 'folglich' (consequently)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"schlussfolgern",src:"to draw a conclusion",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable compound verb.\nSchluss (conclusion) + folgern (to infer).",example:"A: Was k\u00f6nnen wir schlussfolgern?\nB: Wir k\u00f6nnen schlussfolgern, dass Sprache sich ver\u00e4ndert.\nA: Eine wichtige Schlussfolgerung.\nB: Ja, wir schlussfolgern auf Basis der Daten.",exampleSrc:"A: What can we conclude?\nB: We can conclude that language changes.\nA: An important conclusion.\nB: Yes, we draw conclusions on the basis of the data.",funFact:"'Schluss' (conclusion) + 'folgern' (to infer). Inseparable compound verb. Combines the finality of 'Schluss' with the logic of 'folgern.' The noun: Schlussfolgerung."},
{type:"fb",s:"Um eine These zu pruefen, muss man sie kritisch {1}.",a:["reflektieren"],opts:["reflektieren","argumentieren","folgern","eroertern"],hint:"To look back at your own thinking and question it. From Latin 'reflectere' (to bend back).",sSrc:"To examine a thesis, one must critically reflect on it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"reflektieren",src:"to reflect",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. From Latin 'reflectere.'\n'Kritisch reflektieren' (to reflect critically).",example:"A: Hast du \u00fcber die Vorlesung reflektiert?\nB: Ja, ich reflektiere immer danach.\nA: Was hast du reflektiert?\nB: Ob ich die Zusammenh\u00e4nge wirklich verstanden habe.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you reflected on the lecture?\nB: Yes, I always reflect afterwards.\nA: What did you reflect on?\nB: Whether I truly understood the connections.",funFact:"Academic reflection means looking back at your own argument and questioning it. Self-awareness in scholarship. The Latin root 'reflectere' literally meant 'to bend back.' 'Kritisch reflektieren' is a core academic skill."},
{type:"teach",trg:"abstrakt",src:"abstract",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. The opposite of 'konkret.'\n'Abstrakte Begriffe' (abstract concepts).",example:"A: Ist das Thema nicht zu abstrakt?\nB: Abstrakte Themen sind normal in der Linguistik.\nA: Wie macht man Abstraktes konkret?\nB: Mit Beispielen und Daten.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the topic not too abstract?\nB: Abstract topics are normal in linguistics.\nA: How do you make abstract things concrete?\nB: With examples and data.",funFact:"Think of 'abstrakt' as 'drawn away' from the concrete, which is exactly what the Latin root 'abstractus' meant. Abstrakte Begriffe like Freiheit, Gerechtigkeit, Wahrheit. Academic thinking balances abstrakt and konkret."},
{type:"teach",trg:"logisch",src:"logical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Logisch aufgebaut' (logically structured).\nCasually also means 'Obviously!'",example:"A: Ist dein Argument logisch?\nB: Ja, logisch aufgebaut. Schritt f\u00fcr Schritt.\nA: Logisch!\nB: Danke. Logisch zu denken ist das Ziel.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your argument logical?\nB: Yes, logically structured. Step by step.\nA: Obviously!\nB: Thanks. Thinking logically is the goal.",funFact:"From Greek 'logikos.' 'Logisch!' also means 'Obviously!' in casual German. The academic meaning demands rigorous step-by-step reasoning. Two registers, one word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"relevant",src:"relevant",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. 'Relevante Literatur.'\nProfessors love asking: 'Ist das relevant?'",example:"A: Ist dieser Artikel relevant?\nB: Ja, sehr relevant f\u00fcr unsere Forschung.\nA: Warum ist er relevant?\nB: Weil er den Zusammenhang erkl\u00e4rt.",exampleSrc:"A: Is this article relevant?\nB: Yes, very relevant for our research.\nA: Why is it relevant?\nB: Because it explains the connection.",funFact:"German professors love asking: 'Ist das relevant?' If you cannot answer yes with evidence, cut it from your paper. The Latin root 'relevare' meant 'to raise up,' as in lifting what matters."},
{type:"teach",trg:"sachlich",src:"objective, factual, matter-of-fact",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From 'Sache' (thing/matter).\n'Bleiben Sie sachlich' (Stick to the facts).",example:"A: War die Diskussion sachlich?\nB: Ja, alle blieben sachlich.\nA: Sachlich zu diskutieren ist schwer.\nB: Aber wichtig. Sachlich, nicht emotional.",exampleSrc:"A: Was the discussion factual?\nB: Yes, everyone stayed objective.\nA: Discussing factually is hard.\nB: But important. Factual, not emotional.",funFact:"From 'Sache' (thing/matter). Academic register demands sachlich tone. No emotions, no drama, just evidence. 'Bleiben Sie sachlich' is a command every German student hears."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"abstrakt",src:"abstract"},{trg:"logisch",src:"logical"},{trg:"relevant",src:"relevant"},{trg:"sachlich",src:"objective, factual, matter-of-fact"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"wesentlich",src:"essential, substantial",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From 'Wesen' (essence/being).\n'Ein wesentlicher Unterschied.'",example:"A: Gibt es einen wesentlichen Unterschied?\nB: Ja, ein wesentlicher Unterschied besteht in der Methode.\nA: Ist das wesentlich?\nB: Ja, wesentlich f\u00fcr das Ergebnis.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there an essential difference?\nB: Yes, an essential difference lies in the method.\nA: Is that substantial?\nB: Yes, substantial for the result.",funFact:"From 'Wesen' (essence/being). What touches the essence of the matter. More philosophical than 'wichtig' (important). 'Ein wesentlicher Unterschied' carries more weight than 'ein wichtiger Unterschied.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"folglich",src:"consequently, therefore",pos:"adv",gender:null,note:"Adverb. Folge (consequence) + -lich.\nAcademic connector. Signals a conclusion.",example:"A: Die Daten sind eindeutig. Folglich...\nB: Folglich m\u00fcssen wir unsere These anpassen.\nA: Folglich war die erste Hypothese falsch?\nB: Ja, folglich brauchen wir eine neue.",exampleSrc:"A: The data are clear. Consequently...\nB: Consequently we must adjust our thesis.\nA: Consequently the first hypothesis was wrong?\nB: Yes, consequently we need a new one.",funFact:"From 'Folge' (consequence) + '-lich.' 'Folglich m\u00fcssen wir annehmen, dass...' (Consequently we must assume that...). Signals that a conclusion follows from evidence."},
{type:"teach",trg:"h\u00e4tte",src:"would have (Konjunktiv II of haben)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Konjunktiv II of 'haben'. Used in hypothetical past.\n'H\u00e4tte' + Partizip II = something that didn't happen.",example:"A: H\u00e4ttest du den Text gelesen?\nB: H\u00e4tte ich Zeit gehabt, h\u00e4tte ich ihn gelesen.\nA: Und jetzt?\nB: Jetzt ist es zu sp\u00e4t. H\u00e4tte ich frühen gewusst...",exampleSrc:"A: Would you have read the text?\nB: Had I had time, I would have read it.\nA: And now?\nB: Now it is too late. Had I known earlier...",funFact:"H\u00e4tte is the Konjunktiv II of haben. In the hypothetical past (Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit), h\u00e4tte + Partizip II expresses what could have happened but did not. Paired with w\u00e4re for sein-verbs."},
{type:"tip",title:"Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit: Was h\u00e4tte sein k\u00f6nnen",text:"The Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit expresses hypothetical events in the past: things that COULD have happened but did NOT.\n\nFormation uses two auxiliaries, each paired with a Partizip II:\n- h\u00e4tte: used with most verbs (the same ones that take haben in the Perfekt). 'H\u00e4tte ich das gewusst!' (Had I known that!)\n- w\u00e4re: used with movement verbs, change-of-state verbs, and sein itself. 'W\u00e4re ich fr\u00fcher gekommen...' (Had I come earlier...)\n\nExample: 'H\u00e4tte man fr\u00fcher geforscht, w\u00e4re das Ergebnis anders gewesen.' (Had they researched earlier, the result would have been different.)\n\nThe Partizip II always goes at the end of the clause.",deepDive:{title:"When h\u00e4tte vs. w\u00e4re?",text:"H\u00e4tte is used with verbs that take 'haben' in the Perfekt: Ich habe gemacht > Ich h\u00e4tte gemacht. W\u00e4re is used with verbs that take 'sein' in the Perfekt: Ich bin gegangen > Ich w\u00e4re gegangen. The rule is the same as for the Perfekt. Motion verbs (gehen, kommen, fahren), changes of state (werden, sterben, einschlafen), and 'sein' itself use w\u00e4re. Everything else uses h\u00e4tte."}},
{type:"verb_table",title:"Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit (hypothetische Vergangenheit)",groups:[{label:"Mit h\u00e4tte (die meisten Verben)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"h\u00e4tte ... gemacht",src:"I would have done"},{pronoun:"du",form:"h\u00e4ttest ... gemacht",src:"you would have done"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"h\u00e4tte ... gemacht",src:"he/she/it would have done"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"h\u00e4tten ... gemacht",src:"we would have done"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"h\u00e4ttet ... gemacht",src:"you all would have done"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"h\u00e4tten ... gemacht",src:"they/you would have done"}]},{label:"Mit w\u00e4re (sein, Bewegung, Zustandswechsel)",rows:[{pronoun:"ich",form:"w\u00e4re ... gegangen",src:"I would have gone"},{pronoun:"du",form:"w\u00e4r(e)st ... gegangen",src:"you would have gone"},{pronoun:"er/sie/es",form:"w\u00e4re ... gegangen",src:"he/she/it would have gone"},{pronoun:"wir",form:"w\u00e4ren ... gegangen",src:"we would have gone"},{pronoun:"ihr",form:"w\u00e4r(e)t ... gegangen",src:"you all would have gone"},{pronoun:"sie/Sie",form:"w\u00e4ren ... gegangen",src:"they/you would have gone"}]}],note:"H\u00e4tte for verbs that take 'haben' in the Perfekt. W\u00e4re for verbs that take 'sein' in the Perfekt."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"overwhelmed",art:"de-fub-hoersaal-exit",trg:"Neunzig Minuten. Sechzehn Seiten Notizen, davon acht unleserlich. Der Professor hat kein einziges Mal auf die Folien geschaut. Er hat sie auswendig vorgetragen. Ich bin hier richtig.",src:"Ninety minutes. Sixteen pages of notes, eight of them illegible. The professor did not look at the slides once. He recited them from memory. I am in the right place."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'abstrakt'?",opts:["to discuss, to examine thoroughly","the connection, the context","logical","abstract"],ans:"abstract",hint:"The opposite of concrete. Theoretical, not tangible. A Latin loanword."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ist dieser Artikel {1}?",a:["relevant"],opts:["die Entwicklung","relevant","reflektieren","wesentlich"],hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent. Does this source apply to your topic?",sSrc:"Is this article relevant?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'sachlich'?",opts:["the meaning, the significance","to justify, to give reasons","objective, factual, matter-of-fact","would have (Konjunktiv II of haben)"],ans:"objective, factual, matter-of-fact",hint:"Sache (thing/substance) + -lich. Sticking strictly to what can be shown."},
{type:"fb",s:"Gibt es einen {1}en Unterschied?",a:["wesentlich"],opts:["er\\u00f6rtern","folgern","begr\\u00fcnden","wesentlich"],hint:"From Wesen (essence/being) + -lich. Touching the core of the matter.",sSrc:"Is there an essential difference?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'folglich'?",opts:["consequently, therefore","to argue (academically)","to reflect","the development"],ans:"consequently, therefore",hint:"Folge (consequence) + -lich. What logically follows from a premise."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l4",title:"Nominalisierung und Verbalisierung",icon:"\uD83D\uDD04",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Nominalisierung und Verbalisierung",desc:"Master the art of turning verbs into nouns and nouns into verbs. Understand why academic German is so noun-heavy. Learn evaluation vocabulary.",goals:["Master the patterns of Nominalisierung (-ung, -heit, -keit)","Understand Verbalisierung (noun/adjective to verb)","Learn 20 words for evaluation and critical thinking"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Verbesserung",src:"the improvement",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'verbessern' (to improve).\nClassic -ung Nominalisierung.",example:"A: Gibt es eine Verbesserung?\nB: Ja, eine deutliche Verbesserung der Ergebnisse.\nA: Worin besteht die Verbesserung?\nB: Die Methode ist jetzt pr\u00e4ziser.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there an improvement?\nB: Yes, a clear improvement in the results.\nA: What does the improvement consist of?\nB: The method is now more precise.",funFact:"From 'verbessern' (to improve). The -ung suffix transforms any verb into a feminine noun. 'Die Verbesserung der Methode' = 'dass man die Methode verbessert.' Same meaning, different density."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Verschlechterung",src:"the deterioration",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'verschlechtern' (to worsen).\nExact opposite of Verbesserung.",example:"A: Gibt es eine Verschlechterung?\nB: Leider ja, eine Verschlechterung der Qualit\u00e4t.\nA: Seit wann die Verschlechterung?\nB: Die Verschlechterung begann vor zwei Monaten.",exampleSrc:"A: Is there a deterioration?\nB: Unfortunately yes, a deterioration in quality.\nA: Since when the deterioration?\nB: The deterioration began two months ago.",funFact:"From 'verschlechtern' (to worsen). The exact opposite of Verbesserung. German loves these pairs: besser/schlechter becomes Verbesserung/Verschlechterung. Symmetry in language."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Erkl\u00e4rung",src:"the explanation, the declaration",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'erkl\u00e4ren' (to explain).\nAlso: Steuererkl\u00e4rung (tax return).",example:"A: Hast du eine Erkl\u00e4rung daf\u00fcr?\nB: Ja, meine Erkl\u00e4rung ist folgende...\nA: Eine gute Erkl\u00e4rung.\nB: Jede These braucht eine Erkl\u00e4rung.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have an explanation for that?\nB: Yes, my explanation is the following...\nA: A good explanation.\nB: Every thesis needs an explanation.",funFact:"From 'erkl\u00e4ren' (to explain). Also the word for a tax return: Steuererkl\u00e4rung. Explaining yourself to the Finanzamt uses the same word as explaining your thesis."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Begr\u00fcndung",src:"the justification, the reasoning",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'begr\u00fcnden' (to justify).\n'Ohne Begr\u00fcndung' = academic death sentence.",example:"A: Was ist deine Begr\u00fcndung?\nB: Meine Begr\u00fcndung basiert auf den Daten.\nA: Ohne Begr\u00fcndung geht es nicht.\nB: Jede Behauptung braucht eine Begr\u00fcndung.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your justification?\nB: My justification is based on the data.\nA: Without justification it does not work.\nB: Every claim needs a justification.",funFact:"From 'begr\u00fcnden' (to justify). 'Ohne Begr\u00fcndung' is the academic death sentence. Every claim needs its Begr\u00fcndung. No argument survives without one."},
{type:"fb",s:"Das Gegenteil von Verbesserung ist {1}.",a:["Verschlechterung"],opts:["Verschlechterung","Erklaerung","Begruendung","Bewertung"],hint:"If Verbesserung means improvement, what is the exact opposite using the same -ung pattern?",sSrc:"The opposite of improvement is deterioration."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Bewertung",src:"the evaluation, the assessment",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'bewerten' (to evaluate).\n'Die Bewertung der Ergebnisse.'",example:"A: Wie f\u00e4llt die Bewertung aus?\nB: Die Bewertung ist positiv.\nA: Wer macht die Bewertung?\nB: Der Professor gibt die Bewertung.",exampleSrc:"A: How does the evaluation turn out?\nB: The evaluation is positive.\nA: Who does the evaluation?\nB: The professor gives the evaluation.",funFact:"From 'bewerten' (to evaluate). Your Hausarbeit gets a Bewertung. Your professor gives it a Note (grade). The Bewertung determines your academic fate."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Beobachtung",src:"the observation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'beobachten' (to observe).\n'Empirische Beobachtungen.'",example:"A: Was zeigen deine Beobachtungen?\nB: Die Beobachtung zeigt ein klares Muster.\nA: Wie viele Beobachtungen hast du gemacht?\nB: \u00dcber hundert Beobachtungen.",exampleSrc:"A: What do your observations show?\nB: The observation shows a clear pattern.\nA: How many observations have you made?\nB: Over a hundred observations.",funFact:"From 'beobachten' (to observe). The foundation of all science: first you beobachten, then you analysieren. 'Empirische Beobachtungen' are the raw material of research."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die L\u00f6sung",src:"the solution",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'l\u00f6sen' (to solve).\nAlso: liquid solution in chemistry.",example:"A: Hast du eine L\u00f6sung gefunden?\nB: Ja, eine kreative L\u00f6sung.\nA: Was ist die L\u00f6sung?\nB: Die L\u00f6sung liegt in der Methode.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you found a solution?\nB: Yes, a creative solution.\nA: What is the solution?\nB: The solution lies in the method.",funFact:"From 'l\u00f6sen' (to solve/dissolve). Also means a liquid solution in chemistry. Solving is dissolving the problem. 'Eine kreative L\u00f6sung finden' is what every researcher aims for."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Entscheidung",src:"the decision",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'entscheiden' (to decide).\n'Eine wichtige Entscheidung treffen.'",example:"A: Hast du die Entscheidung getroffen?\nB: Ja, die Entscheidung steht fest.\nA: War es eine schwere Entscheidung?\nB: Ja, aber die richtige Entscheidung.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you made the decision?\nB: Yes, the decision is final.\nA: Was it a difficult decision?\nB: Yes, but the right decision.",funFact:"Ent- (un-/dis-) + scheiden (to separate). A decision separates one path from another. You cut away alternatives until one remains. 'Eine wichtige Entscheidung treffen' is a core phrase."},
{type:"mc",q:"Welches Wort beschreibt, dass jemand etwas tun kann?",opts:["die Dankbarkeit","die Faehigkeit","die Entscheidung","die Loesung"],ans:"die Faehigkeit",hint:"An abstract noun formed from the adjective 'faehig' (capable) with the -keit suffix."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die F\u00e4higkeit",src:"the ability, the skill",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. F\u00e4hig (capable) + -keit.\nThe -keit suffix works on adjectives ending in -ig.",example:"A: Welche F\u00e4higkeiten brauchst du?\nB: Analytische F\u00e4higkeiten sind am wichtigsten.\nA: Hast du diese F\u00e4higkeit?\nB: Ich arbeite daran, diese F\u00e4higkeit zu verbessern.",exampleSrc:"A: What skills do you need?\nB: Analytical skills are most important.\nA: Do you have this ability?\nB: I am working on improving this ability.",funFact:"From 'f\u00e4hig' (capable) + '-keit.' The -keit suffix works on adjectives ending in -ig. 'Analytische F\u00e4higkeiten' (analytical skills) are required on every German academic CV. Always feminine."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Dankbarkeit",src:"the gratitude",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Dankbar (grateful) + -keit.\nAbstract qualities love the -keit ending.",example:"A: Empfindest du Dankbarkeit?\nB: Ja, gro\u00dfe Dankbarkeit f\u00fcr diese Chance.\nA: Dankbarkeit ist wichtig.\nB: Ohne Dankbarkeit vergisst man, woher man kommt.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you feel gratitude?\nB: Yes, great gratitude for this chance.\nA: Gratitude is important.\nB: Without gratitude you forget where you come from.",funFact:"'Dankbar' (grateful) + '-keit.' Another -keit nominalization. The adjective 'dankbar' becomes the abstract noun 'Dankbarkeit.' A pattern that creates entire families of abstract nouns."},
{type:"teach",trg:"bewerten",src:"to evaluate, to assign value",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Be- + Wert (value).\n'Wie bewerten Sie dieses Ergebnis?'",example:"A: Wie bewertest du das Ergebnis?\nB: Ich bewerte es positiv.\nA: Kann man das objektiv bewerten?\nB: Man muss es anhand der Kriterien bewerten.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you evaluate the result?\nB: I evaluate it positively.\nA: Can one evaluate it objectively?\nB: One must evaluate it against the criteria.",funFact:"'Be-' + 'Wert' (value). Literally to assign value. The reverse of Bewertung: verb from noun root. 'Wie bewerten Sie dieses Ergebnis?' is the professor's standard question."},
{type:"teach",trg:"beurteilen",src:"to judge, to assess",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Be- + Urteil (judgment).\nSlightly different from bewerten.",example:"A: Wie beurteilst du die Lage?\nB: Ich beurteile sie vorsichtig.\nA: Kann man das fair beurteilen?\nB: Man muss alle Seiten beurteilen.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you assess the situation?\nB: I assess it cautiously.\nA: Can one judge it fairly?\nB: One must assess all sides.",funFact:"'Be-' + 'Urteil' (judgment). Slightly different from bewerten: beurteilen is about judgment, bewerten about assigning value. 'Die Qualit\u00e4t beurteilen' (to assess the quality)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Um Daten systematisch zu analysieren, muss man sie {1}.",a:["auswerten"],opts:["bewerten","beurteilen","auswerten","hinterfragen"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to extract value from raw data. 'Aus' (out) + 'werten' (to value).",sSrc:"To systematically analyze data, one must evaluate them."},

{type:"mc",q:"Wir haben eine Lösung gefunden. Was ist 'die Lösung'?",opts:["the problem","the question","the solution","the difficulty"],ans:"the solution",hint:"The result when a problem is resolved. From 'lösen' meaning to loosen or dissolve."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l4b",title:"Nominalisierung und Verbalisierung (Teil 2)",icon:"\uD83D\uDD04",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Nominalisierung und Verbalisierung (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"auswerten",src:"to evaluate, to analyze (data)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Aus (out) + werten (to value).\n'Daten auswerten' (to analyze data).",example:"A: Hast du die Daten schon ausgewertet?\nB: Ja, ich werte gerade die letzten Daten aus.\nA: Was zeigt die Auswertung?\nB: Die Auswertung best\u00e4tigt die Hypothese.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you analyzed the data yet?\nB: Yes, I am currently analyzing the last data.\nA: What does the analysis show?\nB: The analysis confirms the hypothesis.",funFact:"'Aus' (out) + 'werten' (to value). You extract the value from raw data. Separable: 'Ich werte die Daten aus.' The nominalized form: die Auswertung (the data analysis)."},
{type:"teach",trg:"herausfinden",src:"to find out, to discover",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Heraus (out) + finden (to find).\n'Wir wollen herausfinden, ob...'",example:"A: Was willst du herausfinden?\nB: Ich will herausfinden, ob die These stimmt.\nA: Und? Hast du es herausgefunden?\nB: Ja, ich habe es endlich herausgefunden.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you want to find out?\nB: I want to find out whether the thesis is correct.\nA: And? Have you found out?\nB: Yes, I finally found it out.",funFact:"'Heraus' (out) + 'finden' (to find). The verb of research curiosity. Separable. Strong verb: herausfinden, fand heraus, herausgefunden. Finding what was hidden."},
{type:"teach",trg:"\u00fcberpr\u00fcfen",src:"to verify, to review",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. \u00dcber (over) + pr\u00fcfen (to test).\n'Die Hypothese \u00fcberpr\u00fcfen.'",example:"A: Hast du die Quellen \u00fcberpr\u00fcft?\nB: Ja, ich \u00fcberpr\u00fcfe alles doppelt.\nA: Warum \u00fcberpr\u00fcfen?\nB: Weil man Ergebnisse immer \u00fcberpr\u00fcfen muss.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you verified the sources?\nB: Yes, I double-check everything.\nA: Why verify?\nB: Because you must always verify results.",funFact:"'\u00dcber' (over) + 'pr\u00fcfen' (to test/check). Not separable. Checking something thoroughly by going over it. '\u00dcberpr\u00fcfung' is the nominalized form."},
{type:"teach",trg:"hinterfragen",src:"to question critically, to challenge",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Hinter (behind) + fragen (ask).\n'Ergebnisse hinterfragen.'",example:"A: Sollte man alles hinterfragen?\nB: Ja, kritisch hinterfragen ist wichtig.\nA: Auch die eigenen Ergebnisse?\nB: Besonders die eigenen Ergebnisse muss man hinterfragen.",exampleSrc:"A: Should one question everything?\nB: Yes, questioning critically is important.\nA: Even your own results?\nB: Especially your own results you must question.",funFact:"'Hinter' (behind) + 'fragen' (to ask). Asking what is BEHIND the surface. Not separable. The hallmark of critical thinking in German academia."},
{type:"mc",q:"Im akademischen Deutsch ist 'kritisch' ein positives Wort. Was bedeutet es?",opts:["negativ und ablehnend","gedankenlos und oberflaechlich","schnell und entscheidungsfreudig","sorgfaeltig und reflektiert denkend"],ans:"sorgfaeltig und reflektiert denkend",hint:"In German academia, this word means thoughtful examination, not negativity. A virtue for scholars."},
{type:"teach",trg:"kritisch",src:"critical (positive: thoughtful)",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. In academia, kritisch is POSITIVE.\n'Kritisches Denken' (critical thinking).",example:"A: Bist du kritisch genug?\nB: Ich versuche, immer kritisch zu sein.\nA: Kritisch sein ist eine Tugend.\nB: Ja, kritisches Denken ist das Ziel.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you critical enough?\nB: I try to always be critical.\nA: Being critical is a virtue.\nB: Yes, critical thinking is the goal.",funFact:"From Greek 'kritikos' (able to judge). In German academia, kritisch is positive: it means thoughtful, not negative. 'Seien Sie kritisch' means 'think carefully,' not 'be negative.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"pr\u00e4zise",src:"precise, exact",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Latin 'praecisus' (cut short).\n'Pr\u00e4zise formulieren' (to formulate precisely).",example:"A: Ist das pr\u00e4zise genug?\nB: Nein, formulieren Sie es pr\u00e4ziser.\nA: Wie pr\u00e4zise muss es sein?\nB: So pr\u00e4zise wie m\u00f6glich.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that precise enough?\nB: No, formulate it more precisely.\nA: How precise must it be?\nB: As precise as possible.",funFact:"'Seien Sie präziser' is a margin note every German student dreads. Academic writing demands precision, and vague language is the enemy. The Latin root 'praecisus' meant 'cut short,' trimming away the excess."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nachvollziehbar",src:"comprehensible, traceable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. Nach (after) + vollziehbar (traceable).\n'Ihre Argumentation muss nachvollziehbar sein.'",example:"A: Ist die Argumentation nachvollziehbar?\nB: Ja, jeder Schritt ist nachvollziehbar.\nA: Nachvollziehbar f\u00fcr Laien?\nB: Auch f\u00fcr Laien nachvollziehbar.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the argumentation comprehensible?\nB: Yes, every step is traceable.\nA: Comprehensible for laypeople?\nB: Also comprehensible for laypeople.",funFact:"'Nach' (after) + 'vollziehbar' (executable/traceable). Others must be able to follow your logic step by step. If it is not nachvollziehbar, it is not wissenschaftlich."},
{type:"teach",trg:"methodisch",src:"methodical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. Methode + -isch.\n'Methodisch vorgehen' (to proceed methodically).",example:"A: Gehst du methodisch vor?\nB: Ja, immer methodisch. Struktur ist alles.\nA: Methodisches Arbeiten ist Pflicht.\nB: Ohne methodisches Vorgehen kein Ergebnis.",exampleSrc:"A: Are you proceeding methodically?\nB: Yes, always methodically. Structure is everything.\nA: Methodical work is mandatory.\nB: Without a methodical approach, no result.",funFact:"From 'Methode' + '-isch.' German academia demands methodisches Arbeiten (methodical work) as a baseline, not a bonus. Unmethodisch is never acceptable."},
{type:"fb",s:"Eine gute Argumentation muss {1} sein, damit andere sie Schritt fuer Schritt nachvollziehen koennen.",a:["nachvollziehbar"],opts:["nachvollziehbar","praezise","methodisch","kritisch"],hint:"Others must be able to follow your logic. The adjective built from 'nach' (after) + 'vollziehbar' (traceable).",sSrc:"A good argumentation must be comprehensible so that others can trace it step by step."},
{type:"tip",title:"Nominalisierung: Das komplette Werkzeug",text:"German builds nouns from verbs and adjectives using predictable suffixes. All resulting nouns are feminine.\n\nThe -ung suffix turns verbs into nouns:\n- erkl\u00e4ren becomes Erkl\u00e4rung (explanation)\n- beobachten becomes Beobachtung (observation)\n- bewerten becomes Bewertung (evaluation)\n\nThe -heit suffix turns adjectives into nouns:\n- frei becomes Freiheit (freedom)\n- sicher becomes Sicherheit (security)\n\nAdjectives ending in -ig, -lich, or -bar take -keit instead:\n- f\u00e4hig becomes F\u00e4higkeit (ability)\n- dankbar becomes Dankbarkeit (gratitude)\n\nVerbalization works in the opposite direction, turning nouns and adjectives into verbs:\n- Analyse becomes analysieren, klar becomes kl\u00e4ren, Kritik becomes kritisieren\n\nAcademic German prefers the nominal style. Spoken German prefers the verbal style.",deepDive:{title:"Nominal vs. verbal style",text:"The nominal style compresses: 'Die Verbesserung der Methode f\u00fchrte zur Optimierung der Ergebnisse.' The verbal style unpacks: 'Weil man die Methode verbessert hat, konnte man die Ergebnisse optimieren.' Both say the same thing. The nominal style saves words, sounds more formal, but is harder to read. The verbal style is clearer but longer. Good academic texts mix both styles."}},
{type:"mc",q:"'H\u00e4tte die Begr\u00fcndung \u00fcberzeugender gewirkt, w\u00e4re die Bewertung besser ausgefallen.' Welche Grammatikmerkmale werden kombiniert?",opts:["Nur einfache Nominalisierung","Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit + Nominalisierung","Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit ohne jede Nominalform","Pr\u00e4teritum mit einfacher Nominalisierung"],ans:"Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit + Nominalisierung",hint:"'Hätte ... gewirkt' and 'wäre ... ausgefallen' are hypothetical past. 'Begründung' and 'Bewertung' are nominalized forms."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Auswertung",src:"the evaluation, the analysis",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Nominalization of auswerten. The -ung suffix always creates feminine nouns.",example:"Die Auswertung der Daten dauert zwei Wochen.",exampleSrc:"The evaluation of the data takes two weeks.",funFact:"German loves turning verbs into nouns with -ung. It is one of the most productive word-formation patterns in the language."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} der Ergebnisse dauerte drei Monate.",a:["Auswertung"],opts:["Auswerten","Ausgewertet","Auswertung","Wertung"],hint:"Nominalize the verb 'auswerten' using the most productive German noun-forming suffix.",sSrc:"The evaluation of the results took three months."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Man kann die Qualit\u00e4t {1} und die Ergebnisse kritisch {2}.",blanks:{"1":"bewerten","2":"hinterfragen"},pool:["bewerten","hinterfragen","Bewertung","Hinterfragung","bewertet","hinterfragt"],hint:"Both blanks are infinitive verbs. One expresses qualitative judgment, the other expresses critical examination from behind the surface."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Verbesserung",src:"verbessern"},{trg:"die Erkl\u00e4rung",src:"erkl\u00e4ren"},{trg:"die Bewertung",src:"bewerten"},{trg:"die Beobachtung",src:"beobachten"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'herausfinden'?",opts:["to find out, to discover","to evaluate, to analyze (data)","the ability, the skill","comprehensible, traceable"],ans:"to find out, to discover",hint:"Heraus- (out) + the verb for locating. To uncover something through investigation."},

{type:"fb",s:"Der Professor muss die Ergebnisse noch {1}.",a:["überprüfen"],opts:["überprüfen","bewerten","herausfinden","auswerten"],hint:"A verb meaning to verify or review, checking that something is correct.",sSrc:"The professor still needs to verify the results."},

{type:"mc",q:"Die Anweisungen müssen präzise formuliert sein. Was bedeutet 'präzise'?",opts:["general","vague","precise, exact","simple"],ans:"precise, exact",hint:"Accurate and clearly defined, leaving no room for ambiguity."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l5",title:"In der Mensa",icon:"🍽️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"In der Mensa",desc:"The Mensa: Schnitzel for 2.50 EUR and new friendships. Learn vocabulary for student life, practice Konjunktiv II past in conversation, and chat with fellow students.",goals:["Learn 20 new words about student life and exams","Practice Konjunktiv II past in casual conversations","Discuss academic life with fellow students"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-uni-mensa-trays",trg:"Die Mensa. Lange Tische, das Klappern von Tabletts, der Geruch von Schnitzel für 2.50 EUR. Verumius schaut auf sein Tablett. Schnitzel, Kartoffelsalat, ein Getraenk. Gesamt: 3.20 EUR. Er blinzelt.",src:"The Mensa. Long tables, the clatter of trays, the smell of Schnitzel for 2.50 EUR. Verumius looks at his tray. Schnitzel, potato salad, a drink. Total: 3.20 EUR. He blinks."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"surprised",art:"de-uni-mensa-tray-closeup",trg:"Das kostet nur 3.20? In Istanbul hätte ich dafür nicht mal einen Kaffee bekommen.",src:"This costs only 3.20? In Istanbul I would not have even gotten a coffee for that."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"communal",art:"de-uni-mensa-table",trg:"Er setzt sich an einen langen Tisch. Eine Studentin stellt sich vor. 'Hi, ich bin Jana. Linguistik, drittes Semester. Und du?'",src:"He sits down at a long table. A student introduces herself. 'Hi, I am Jana. Linguistics, third semester. And you?'"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"happy",art:"de-uni-mensa-conversation",trg:"Verumius. Auch Linguistik. Erstes Semester. Wäre ich früher nach Deutschland gekommen, hätte ich früher angefangen.",src:"Verumius. Also linguistics. First semester. Had I come to Germany earlier, I would have started sooner."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Semesterferien",src:"the semester break",pos:"noun",gender:"pl",note:"Always plural. Semester + Ferien (holidays).\n'In den Semesterferien' (during semester break).",example:"A: Was machst du in den Semesterferien?\nB: Ich schreibe meine Hausarbeit.\nA: Das klingt nicht nach Ferien.\nB: In den Semesterferien ist man nie wirklich frei.",exampleSrc:"A: What are you doing during semester break?\nB: I am writing my term paper.\nA: That does not sound like a holiday.\nB: During semester break you are never truly free.",funFact:"German students call them 'vorlesungsfreie Zeit' (lecture-free time), but they are NOT free: exam preparation, internships, and Hausarbeiten fill every day. The name is misleading by design."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Stipendium",src:"the scholarship",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Plural: Stipendien.\nFrom Latin 'stipendium' (tax/payment).",example:"A: Hast du ein Stipendium?\nB: Ja, das Deutschlandstipendium.\nA: Wie viel bekommst du?\nB: 300 EUR im Monat. Nicht viel, aber es hilft.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have a scholarship?\nB: Yes, the Deutschlandstipendium.\nA: How much do you get?\nB: 300 EUR per month. Not much, but it helps.",funFact:"Germany offers Stipendien from 13 major foundations. The Deutschlandstipendium gives 300 EUR per month. Not enough to live on, but prestigious on a CV. Half comes from the government, half from private donors."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Studentenwohnheim",src:"the student dormitory",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Studenten + Wohn (living) + Heim (home).\nA triple compound noun.",example:"A: Wohnst du im Studentenwohnheim?\nB: Ja, im dritten Stock.\nA: Wie ist es?\nB: Klein, aber die Miete ist guenstig.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you live in the student dormitory?\nB: Yes, on the third floor.\nA: How is it?\nB: Small, but the rent is affordable.",funFact:"Rooms cost 200-400 EUR per month. Shared kitchen, shared bathroom, shared everything. A German student rite of passage. Waiting lists can be months long. The Studentenwerk manages most Wohnheime."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Prüfung",src:"the exam, the test",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'prüfen' (to test).\n'Eine Prüfung bestehen' (to pass an exam).",example:"A: Wann ist deine nächsste Prüfung?\nB: In zwei Wochen.\nA: Bist du vorbereitet?\nB: Noch nicht. Ich muss noch viel lernen.",exampleSrc:"A: When is your next exam?\nB: In two weeks.\nA: Are you prepared?\nB: Not yet. I still have a lot to study.",funFact:"German university exams can be oral (mündlich) or written (schriftlich). Failing twice at some universities means you cannot repeat the course. The Prüfungsangst (exam anxiety) is real and even has its own Wikipedia page."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Klausur",src:"the written exam",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Latin 'clausura' (enclosure).\nAlways written, always timed.",example:"A: Wie lief die Klausur?\nB: Schwer. Drei Stunden, fünf Fragen.\nA: Hast du alles geschafft?\nB: Fast. Die letzte Frage war zu komplex.",exampleSrc:"A: How did the written exam go?\nB: Hard. Three hours, five questions.\nA: Did you finish everything?\nB: Almost. The last question was too complex.",funFact:"Different from Prüfung: a Klausur is always written, always timed, always in a supervised room. 'Klausur schreiben' (to take a written exam). The word comes from Latin 'clausura' (enclosure), because you are locked in."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"das Stipendium",src:"the scholarship"},{trg:"das Studentenwohnheim",src:"the student dormitory"},{trg:"die Prüfung",src:"the exam, the test"},{trg:"die Klausur",src:"the written exam"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Hausarbeit",src:"the term paper, the research paper",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Haus (home) + Arbeit (work).\nTypically 15-25 pages with strict formatting.",example:"A: Hast du schon mit der Hausarbeit angefangen?\nB: Nein, ich suche noch nach einer Forschungsfrage.\nA: Die Deadline ist in vier Wochen.\nB: Ich weiß. Der Druck wächst.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you started the term paper yet?\nB: No, I am still looking for a research question.\nA: The deadline is in four weeks.\nB: I know. The pressure is growing.",funFact:"Written at home, hence the name. Typically 15-25 pages. German Hausarbeiten have strict formatting rules: margins, font size, citation style, everything regulated. The Deckblatt (cover page) alone has rules."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist der Unterschied zwischen einem Stipendium und einem Studentenwohnheim?",opts:["Beides ist eine finanzielle Unterstuetzung","Ein Stipendium ist Geld, ein Wohnheim ist eine Unterkunft","Beides ist eine Art von Pruefung","Ein Wohnheim ist teurer als ein Stipendium"],ans:"Ein Stipendium ist Geld, ein Wohnheim ist eine Unterkunft",hint:"One provides financial support, the other provides a place to live. Two different aspects of student life."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Kommilitone",src:"the fellow student (male)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. N-Deklination: Kommilitone, Kommilitonen.\nFrom Latin 'commilito' (fellow soldier).",example:"A: Kennst du viele Kommilitonen?\nB: Ja, in meinem Seminar sind nette Kommilitonen.\nA: Arbeitet ihr zusammen?\nB: Manchmal. Wir bilden Lerngruppen.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you know many fellow students?\nB: Yes, there are nice fellow students in my seminar.\nA: Do you work together?\nB: Sometimes. We form study groups.",funFact:"Students as 'comrades-in-arms' in the battle of education. N-Deklination: den Kommilitonen, dem Kommilitonen. Only used for university students, not school pupils. The word carries a sense of shared struggle."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Kommilitonin",src:"the fellow student (female)",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Kommilitone + '-in.'\nPlural: Kommilitoninnen.",example:"A: Jana ist meine Kommilitonin.\nB: Studiert sie auch Linguistik?\nA: Ja, drittes Semester.\nB: Eine erfahrene Kommilitonin also.",exampleSrc:"A: Jana is my fellow student.\nB: Does she also study linguistics?\nA: Yes, third semester.\nB: An experienced fellow student then.",funFact:"The feminine form follows the standard '-in' pattern. The gender-neutral trend uses 'Kommiliton*innen' or 'Mitstudierende' (fellow students). But Kommilitone/Kommilitonin persists in everyday university language."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} ist immer eine schriftliche, zeitlich begrenzte Pruefung.",a:["Klausur"],opts:["Klausur","Pruefung","Hausarbeit","Sprechstunde"],hint:"Always written, always timed, always supervised. From Latin 'clausura' (enclosure).",sSrc:"The written exam is always a written, time-limited test."},

{type:"mc",q:"In den Semesterferien schreibt er seine Hausarbeit. Was sind 'die Semesterferien'?",opts:["the lecture period","the semester break","the final exams","the enrollment period"],ans:"the semester break",hint:"The pause between academic periods when no lectures are held. Students often write papers or travel during this time."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l5b",title:"In der Mensa (Teil 2)",icon:"🍽️",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"In der Mensa (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sprechstunde",src:"the office hours",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Sprech (speaking) + Stunde (hour).\n'In die Sprechstunde gehen' (to go to office hours).",example:"A: Warst du schon in der Sprechstunde?\nB: Ja, letzte Woche beim Professor.\nA: Hat er dir geholfen?\nB: Ja, er hat meine Gliederung besprochen.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you been to office hours yet?\nB: Yes, last week at the professor's.\nA: Did he help you?\nB: Yes, he discussed my outline.",funFact:"Every German professor holds Sprechstunden. You must usually sign up in advance on a list outside the office door. 'Sprechstunde' is also used for doctors. The concept: a designated hour for speaking."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Prüfungsordnung",src:"the examination regulations",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Prüfung + Ordnung (order/regulation).\nThe bureaucratic rulebook for all exams.",example:"A: Hast du die Prüfungsordnung gelesen?\nB: Ja, sie ist 40 Seiten lang.\nA: 40 Seiten?\nB: Deutsche Gruendlichkeit. Jede Regel steht drin.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you read the examination regulations?\nB: Yes, it is 40 pages long.\nA: 40 pages?\nB: German thoroughness. Every rule is in there.",funFact:"Every Studiengang has one. It specifies how many exam attempts, what percentage to pass, which deadlines. German Ordnung at its finest. Students who do not read their Prüfungsordnung regret it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"einreichen",src:"to submit",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Ein (in) + reichen (to hand/reach).\n'Die Hausarbeit einreichen' (to submit the paper).",example:"A: Wann musst du die Arbeit einreichen?\nB: Bis nächssten Freitag.\nA: Schaffst du das?\nB: Ich muss. Die Frist ist die Frist.",exampleSrc:"A: When do you have to submit the paper?\nB: By next Friday.\nA: Will you manage?\nB: I must. A deadline is a deadline.",funFact:"You 'reach it in' to the professor or department. Missing the Einreichungsfrist (submission deadline) typically means zero points. No exceptions, no extensions. German academic culture values punctuality above almost everything."},
{type:"teach",trg:"spezialisieren",src:"to specialize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. Reflexive: 'sich auf etwas spezialisieren.'\nFrom Latin 'specialis.'",example:"A: Worauf spezialisierst du dich?\nB: Ich spezialisiere mich auf Computerlinguistik.\nA: Das ist ein spannendes Fachgebiet.\nB: Ja, die Spezialisierung macht mir Spass.",exampleSrc:"A: What do you specialize in?\nB: I specialize in computational linguistics.\nA: That is an exciting field.\nB: Yes, the specialization is fun for me.",funFact:"Reflexive with 'sich auf.' From the general to the specific. 'Spezialisierung' is the nominalized form. German universities encourage early Spezialisierung compared to the broader American liberal arts model."},
{type:"mc",q:"Wohin geht man, wenn man eine Frage an den Professor hat?",opts:["in die Mensa","in die Sprechstunde","zur Pruefungsordnung","zum Studentenwohnheim"],ans:"in die Sprechstunde",hint:"The designated hour for speaking with a professor. You usually sign up on a list outside the office door."},
{type:"teach",trg:"referieren",src:"to give a presentation, to present",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb. 'Über ein Thema referieren.'\nA Referat is a student presentation.",example:"A: Wer referiert nächsste Woche?\nB: Ich. Über Nominalisierung.\nA: Bist du nervoes?\nB: Ein bisschen. Mein erstes Referat auf Deutsch.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is presenting next week?\nB: Me. About nominalization.\nA: Are you nervous?\nB: A little. My first presentation in German.",funFact:"A Referat is a student presentation, typically 15-20 minutes with a handout. 'Wer referiert nächsste Woche?' is the professor's dreaded question. The word comes from Latin 'referre' (to report). Academic ritual."},
{type:"teach",trg:"publizieren",src:"to publish",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb.\n'Einen Artikel publizieren' (to publish an article).",example:"A: Hast du schon etwas publiziert?\nB: Noch nicht. Erst nach dem Master.\nA: Der Professor hat viel publiziert.\nB: Ja, über 50 Artikel. Das ist beeindruckend.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you published anything yet?\nB: Not yet. Only after the Master's.\nA: The professor has published a lot.\nB: Yes, over 50 articles. That is impressive.",funFact:"The academic pressure: 'Publish or perish' is 'Publiziere oder gehe unter' in German. Publications are academic currency. Your Publikationsliste (list of publications) determines your career. Quantity and quality both count."},
{type:"teach",trg:"promovieren",src:"to earn a doctorate, to do a PhD",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb.\n'Sie promoviert in Physik' (she is doing her PhD in physics).",example:"A: Moechtest du promovieren?\nB: Vielleicht. Erst den Master abschließen.\nA: Wie lange dauert eine Promotion?\nB: Drei bis fünf Jahre, je nach Fachbereich.",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like to do a PhD?\nB: Maybe. First finish the Master's.\nA: How long does a doctorate take?\nB: Three to five years, depending on the department.",funFact:"German doctoral titles (Dr.) are used in everyday life, even on doorbells and ID cards. 'Herr Doktor' is a form of address. The Promotion (doctorate) is the highest academic achievement, and Germans wear it proudly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zuverlässiig",src:"reliable",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. Zu (to) + verlaessig (relying).\n'Zuverlässiige Quellen' (reliable sources).",example:"A: Ist Wikipedia eine zuverlässiige Quelle?\nB: Für den Einstieg ja, aber nicht als einzige.\nA: Was ist zuverlässiiger?\nB: Fachzeitschriften und Primaerquellen.",exampleSrc:"A: Is Wikipedia a reliable source?\nB: For a starting point yes, but not as the only one.\nA: What is more reliable?\nB: Academic journals and primary sources.",funFact:"Academic writing demands zuverlässiige sources. Wikipedia alone is never zuverlässiig enough for a Hausarbeit. The adjective also describes people: 'Er ist zuverlässiig' (He is reliable). A high compliment in German culture."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wer auf Deutsch einen akademischen Titel erwerben will, muss {1}.",a:["promovieren"],opts:["promovieren","publizieren","referieren","einreichen"],hint:"The verb for earning a doctorate (PhD). German doctoral titles appear on doorbells and ID cards.",sSrc:"Those who want to earn an academic title in German must do a PhD."},
{type:"teach",trg:"fundiert",src:"well-founded, substantiated",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective/participle. From Latin 'fundare' (to found).\n'Fundierte Argumentation' (well-founded argumentation).",example:"A: Wie muss eine gute These sein?\nB: Fundiert. Jede Behauptung braucht Belege.\nA: Was bedeutet 'fundiert' genau?\nB: Auf einem soliden Fundament aufgebaut.",exampleSrc:"A: How must a good thesis be?\nB: Well-founded. Every claim needs evidence.\nA: What does 'fundiert' mean exactly?\nB: Built on a solid foundation.",funFact:"Your claims need a Fundament (foundation). A fundierte Studie is one built on solid evidence. The opposite: 'unbefundiert' or 'haltlos' (baseless). In German academia, unfundierte claims are the cardinal sin."},
{type:"teach",trg:"komplex",src:"complex",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Latin 'complexus' (intertwined).\n'Ein komplexes Thema' (a complex topic).",example:"A: Die Forschungsfrage ist ziemlich komplex.\nB: Ja, aber Komplexitaet ist kein Grund aufzugeben.\nA: Wie gehst du damit um?\nB: Ich zerlege das Komplexe in einfache Teile.",exampleSrc:"A: The research question is quite complex.\nB: Yes, but complexity is no reason to give up.\nA: How do you deal with it?\nB: I break the complex into simple parts.",funFact:"Academic code for 'this will be difficult.' 'Die Komplexitaet' (the complexity) is the nominalized form. German scholars love to call problems 'komplex' rather than 'schwierig.' It sounds more respectful of the challenge."},
{type:"teach",trg:"stichhaltig",src:"sound, valid (of arguments)",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. Stich (stab) + haltig (holding).\n'Ein stichhaltiges Argument' (a sound argument).",example:"A: Ist das Argument stichhaltig?\nB: Ja, es hält jeder Kritik stand.\nA: Woher weißt du das?\nB: Ich habe es aus drei Perspektiven überprüft.",exampleSrc:"A: Is the argument sound?\nB: Yes, it withstands any criticism.\nA: How do you know?\nB: I checked it from three perspectives.",funFact:"Literally: an argument that 'holds up under stabbing.' Battle-tested logic. If your Argument is stichhaltig, no one can poke holes in it. The metaphor is beautifully physical for something purely intellectual."},
{type:"teach",trg:"umfassend",src:"comprehensive",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective/participle. Um (around) + fassend (grasping).\n'Eine umfassende Studie' (a comprehensive study).",example:"A: Wie gründlich war die Untersuchung?\nB: Sehr umfassend. Alle Aspekte wurden berücksichtigt.\nA: Das ist beeindruckend.\nB: Umfassende Forschung braucht Zeit.",exampleSrc:"A: How thorough was the investigation?\nB: Very comprehensive. All aspects were considered.\nA: That is impressive.\nB: Comprehensive research takes time.",funFact:"Grasping something from all sides. 'Umfassend' means nothing is left out. The prefix 'um-' (around) creates the image of wrapping your arms around an entire topic. The ultimate academic compliment for a study."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Nach der {1} muss ich die {2} bis Freitag einreichen.",blanks:{"1":"Vorlesung","2":"Hausarbeit"},pool:["Vorlesung","Hausarbeit","Mensa","Stipendium","Prüfung","Hoersaal"],hint:"After the class, the written assignment must be submitted. Two university-specific nouns."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"content",art:"de-uni-mensa-tray-empty",trg:"Verumius schiebt das leere Tablett zur\u00fcck. 3.20 EUR f\u00fcr ein warmes Essen, neue Bekanntschaften und das Gef\u00fchl, dazuzugeh\u00f6ren. Die Mensa ist kein Restaurant. Sie ist eine Institution.",src:"Verumius pushes the empty tray back. 3.20 EUR for a warm meal, new acquaintances, and the feeling of belonging. The Mensa is not a restaurant. It is an institution."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"reflective",art:"de-uni-mensa-window",trg:"Jana hat mir den Tipp gegeben: die Bibliothek im dritten Stock hat die besten Arbeitspl\u00e4tze. H\u00e4tte ich sie nicht in der Mensa getroffen, w\u00fcsste ich das nicht. So funktioniert Uni: man lernt nebenbei.",src:"Jana gave me the tip: the library on the third floor has the best workspaces. Had I not met her in the Mensa, I would not know that. This is how university works: you learn on the side."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'spezialisieren'?",opts:["the scholarship","the examination regulations","to publish","to specialize"],ans:"to specialize",hint:"Near-identical in English. Latin: specialis (of a particular kind)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ist Wikipedia eine {1}e Quelle?",a:["zuverlässiig"],opts:["die Hausarbeit","das Studentenwohnheim","spezialisieren","zuverlässiig"],hint:"Zu- + verlassen (to rely on) + -ig. Someone you can depend on fully.",sSrc:"Is Wikipedia a reliable source?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'fundiert'?",opts:["well-founded, substantiated","the student dormitory","complex","the fellow student (male)"],ans:"well-founded, substantiated",hint:"Latin: fundare (to found). Built on a solid base of evidence."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die Forschungsfrage ist ziemlich {1}.",a:["komplex"],opts:["die Prüfungsordnung","das Stipendium","die Prüfung","komplex"],hint:"Cognate of English 'complex.' Latin: complexus (woven together).",sSrc:"The research question is quite complex."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'stichhaltig'?",opts:["the scholarship","the examination regulations","sound, valid (of arguments)","to submit"],ans:"sound, valid (of arguments)",hint:"Stich (stab/prick) + haltig (holding). Reasoning that holds up under pressure."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sehr {1}. Alle Aspekte wurden berücksichtigt.",a:["umfassend"],opts:["promovieren","publizieren","stichhaltig","umfassend"],hint:"Um- (around) + fassend (grasping). Encompassing everything within scope.",sSrc:"Very comprehensive. All aspects were considered."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l6",title:"Die Hausarbeit",icon:"📚",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Hausarbeit",desc:"Verumius meets Yilmaz in the university library. His advisor helps with the Hausarbeit. Learn vocabulary for academic writing, practice all three grammar constructions, and understand German citation rules.",goals:["Learn 20 new words for academic writing","Practice Konjunktiv II past, Nominalisierung, and Verbalisierung","Understand German citation and plagiarism rules"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"studious",art:"de-uni-library-reading",trg:"Universitaetsbibliothek. Lesesaal mit langen Holztischen und gruenen Leselampen. Buecher tuermen sich um Verumius. Yilmaz sitzt ihm gegenüber. Ihre Beziehung hat sich verändert: vom Lehrer zum Berater, vom Mentor zum Fast-Gleichgestellten.",src:"University library. Reading room with long wooden tables and green reading lamps. Books pile up around Verumius. Yilmaz sits across from him. Their relationship has evolved: from teacher to advisor, from mentor to near-equal."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"collegial",art:"de-uni-yilmaz-advisor",trg:"Verumius, deine Gliederung ist gut. Aber die Einleitung braucht eine klarere Forschungsfrage. Und vergiss die Fussnoten nicht.",src:"Verumius, your outline is good. But the introduction needs a clearer research question. And do not forget the footnotes."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"thinking",art:"de-uni-verumius-books",trg:"Hätte ich gewusst, wie streng die Regeln sind, hätte ich früher mit der Recherche begonnen.",src:"Had I known how strict the rules are, I would have started the research earlier."},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"encouraging",art:"de-uni-yilmaz-encouraging",trg:"Jede Behauptung braucht einen Nachweis. Jedes Zitat eine Quellenangabe. Kein Plagiat. Das ist die Grundlage wissenschaftlichen Arbeitens.",src:"Every claim needs proof. Every quote needs a source citation. No plagiarism. That is the foundation of academic work."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Diplomarbeit",src:"the diploma thesis",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Diplom + Arbeit.\nThe old German degree thesis before the Bologna reform.",example:"A: Hat dein Vater eine Diplomarbeit geschrieben?\nB: Ja, in Ingenieurwissenschaften.\nA: Gibt es das Diplom noch?\nB: Nein, jetzt gibt es Bachelor und Master.",exampleSrc:"A: Did your father write a diploma thesis?\nB: Yes, in engineering.\nA: Does the diploma still exist?\nB: No, now there is Bachelor's and Master's.",funFact:"Many Germans over 40 still proudly cite their Diplomarbeit. The Bologna reform replaced the Diplom with Bachelor and Master around 2010. The Diplom-Ingenieur (Dipl.-Ing.) title is a source of generational pride."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Dissertation",src:"the doctoral thesis",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Latin 'dissertatio' (discussion).\n'An der Dissertation schreiben' (to be writing one's doctoral thesis).",example:"A: Wie lange schreibt man an einer Dissertation?\nB: Drei bis sieben Jahre.\nA: So lange?\nB: Ja, eine Dissertation ist ein Buch.",exampleSrc:"A: How long does one write a doctoral thesis?\nB: Three to seven years.\nA: That long?\nB: Yes, a dissertation is a book.",funFact:"German Dissertationen are published as books, often by academic publishers. Writing one can last 3-7 years. The Rigorosum or Disputation (oral defense) is the final hurdle. Several German politicians lost their Dr. titles due to Dissertations-Plagiate."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Literaturverzeichnis",src:"the bibliography",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Literatur + Verzeichnis (index/list).\nAlphabetically ordered list of all sources.",example:"A: Wie viele Quellen stehen in deinem Literaturverzeichnis?\nB: Über dreissig.\nA: Das ist eine Menge.\nB: Jede einzelne Quelle muss nachprüfbar sein.",exampleSrc:"A: How many sources are in your bibliography?\nB: Over thirty.\nA: That is a lot.\nB: Every single source must be verifiable.",funFact:"Every German Hausarbeit ends with one. Alphabetically ordered by author last name. Missing a source equals academic dishonesty. The Literaturverzeichnis is the proof that you did your homework. Literally."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fussnote",src:"the footnote",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Fuss (foot) + Note (note).\nGerman academic writing uses footnotes extensively.",example:"A: Wie viele Fussnoten hat deine Arbeit?\nB: Schon über fünfzig.\nA: Fünfzig Fussnoten?\nB: Ja, jede Behauptung braucht eine Fussnote.",exampleSrc:"A: How many footnotes does your paper have?\nB: Already over fifty.\nA: Fifty footnotes?\nB: Yes, every claim needs a footnote.",funFact:"Some pages in German academic writing have more footnote text than main text. Fussnoten prove you did your research. They contain citations, cross-references, and additional commentary. A Hausarbeit without Fussnoten is incomplete."},
{type:"fb",s:"Am Ende einer Hausarbeit steht das {1} mit allen Quellen.",a:["Literaturverzeichnis"],opts:["Literaturverzeichnis","Plagiat","Nachweis","Fussnote"],hint:"The alphabetically ordered list of all sources used. A compound: literature + directory.",sSrc:"At the end of a term paper stands the bibliography with all sources."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Einleitung",src:"the introduction",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Ein (in) + Leitung (leading).\n'In der Einleitung stellen Sie Ihre These vor.'",example:"A: Was gehört in die Einleitung?\nB: Die Forschungsfrage, die Methode, die Gliederung.\nA: Und die These?\nB: Ja, die These kommt am Ende der Einleitung.",exampleSrc:"A: What belongs in the introduction?\nB: The research question, the method, the outline.\nA: And the thesis?\nB: Yes, the thesis comes at the end of the introduction.",funFact:"The Einleitung leads the reader into your argument. It must contain: Forschungsfrage, Methode, Gliederung, and your central These. A good Einleitung is a contract with the reader about what they will receive."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gliederung",src:"the outline, the structure",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From 'gliedern' (to structure).\nNumbered: 1., 1.1, 1.1.1, etc.",example:"A: Hast du schon eine Gliederung?\nB: Ja, drei Hauptkapitel mit Unterkapiteln.\nA: Zeig mir die Gliederung.\nB: Hier: Einleitung, Hauptteil, Schluss.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have an outline yet?\nB: Yes, three main chapters with subchapters.\nA: Show me the outline.\nB: Here: introduction, main body, conclusion.",funFact:"German Hausarbeiten require a detailed Gliederung with numbered sections: 1., 1.1, 1.1.1. The Gliederung IS the argument in miniature. Professors often ask to see the Gliederung before you start writing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Nachweis",src:"the proof, the evidence",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Nach (after) + Weis (showing).\n'Einen Nachweis erbringen' (to provide proof).",example:"A: Hast du einen Nachweis für diese Behauptung?\nB: Ja, drei Studien belegen das.\nA: Gut. Ohne Nachweis geht nichts.\nB: Das habe ich gelernt.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have proof for this claim?\nB: Yes, three studies support it.\nA: Good. Nothing works without proof.\nB: I have learned that.",funFact:"Academic and bureaucratic German. Your Leistungsnachweis proves you passed a course. Your Sprachnachweis proves your language level. Germany loves Nachweise: written proof for everything. Without a Nachweis, it did not happen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Plagiat",src:"the plagiarism",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Latin 'plagiarius' (kidnapper).\nGerman universities scan every submission.",example:"A: Was passiert bei einem Plagiat?\nB: Man fällt durch. Im schlimmsten Fall: Exmatrikulation.\nA: So streng?\nB: Ja. Plagiat ist in Deutschland ein schweres Vergehen.",exampleSrc:"A: What happens with plagiarism?\nB: You fail. In the worst case: expulsion.\nA: That strict?\nB: Yes. Plagiarism is a serious offense in Germany.",funFact:"German universities take Plagiate extremely seriously. Software scans every submission. Several German politicians lost their doctoral titles to Plagiat scandals, including a former defense minister. The word comes from Latin for 'kidnapper.'"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was muss man in der Einleitung einer Hausarbeit angeben?",opts:["Nur den Titel und das genaue Abgabedatum","Die Forschungsfrage, Methode und Gliederung","Alle Ergebnisse und die vollstaendige Schlussfolgerung","Die vollstaendige Analyse aller verwendeten Daten"],ans:"Die Forschungsfrage, Methode und Gliederung",hint:"The introduction is a contract with the reader. It states what you will investigate, how, and in what order."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l6b",title:"Die Hausarbeit (Teil 2)",icon:"📚",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Die Hausarbeit (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Recherche",src:"the research, the investigation",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From French 'recherche' (search).\nMore specific than Forschung.",example:"A: Wie weit bist du mit der Recherche?\nB: Fast fertig. Ich habe alle Quellen gefunden.\nA: Gruendliche Recherche ist die halbe Arbeit.\nB: Das stimmt. Die Recherche hat Wochen gedauert.",exampleSrc:"A: How far along are you with the research?\nB: Almost done. I found all sources.\nA: Thorough research is half the work.\nB: That is true. The research took weeks.",funFact:"More specific than Forschung: Recherche is the active search for information. Forschung is the broader scientific endeavor. Journalists do Recherche too. 'Gruendliche Recherche' (thorough research) is the prerequisite for everything academic."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Reihenfolge",src:"the order, the sequence",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Reihen (rows) + Folge (sequence).\n'In der richtigen Reihenfolge' (in the correct order).",example:"A: In welcher Reihenfolge schreibe ich die Kapitel?\nB: Einleitung zuletzt. Erst den Hauptteil.\nA: Wirklich? Die Einleitung zuletzt?\nB: Ja, so kennt man die richtige Reihenfolge.",exampleSrc:"A: In what order do I write the chapters?\nB: Introduction last. First the main body.\nA: Really? The introduction last?\nB: Yes, that way you know the right sequence.",funFact:"The order in which things follow in a row. German loves compound precision. 'In chronologischer Reihenfolge' (in chronological order), 'in alphabetischer Reihenfolge' (in alphabetical order). The concept of order has its own compound word."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verfassen",src:"to write, to author",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. Ver- + fassen (to grasp/compose).\nMore formal than 'schreiben.'",example:"A: Wie lange hast du gebraucht, den Text zu verfassen?\nB: Drei Wochen für den ersten Entwurf.\nA: Und dann?\nB: Dann habe ich ihn überarbeitet.",exampleSrc:"A: How long did it take you to write the text?\nB: Three weeks for the first draft.\nA: And then?\nB: Then I revised it.",funFact:"More formal than 'schreiben.' You verfassen a Hausarbeit. You schreiben a WhatsApp message. Academic register demands 'verfassen' for serious texts. 'Der Verfasser' (the author) is the formal word for who wrote it."},
{type:"teach",trg:"paraphrasieren",src:"to paraphrase",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb.\nRestating ideas in your own words.",example:"A: Darf ich den Autor direkt zitieren?\nB: Ja, aber besser ist paraphrasieren.\nA: Was ist der Unterschied?\nB: Beim Paraphrasieren formulierst du die Idee neu.",exampleSrc:"A: May I quote the author directly?\nB: Yes, but it is better to paraphrase.\nA: What is the difference?\nB: When paraphrasing you reformulate the idea.",funFact:"Essential academic skill: restating ideas in your own words while keeping the meaning. Bad paraphrasieren too close to the original equals Plagiat. German professors can spot lazy paraphrasing instantly."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zitieren",src:"to quote, to cite",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb. From Latin 'citare' (to summon).\n'Korrekt zitieren' (to cite correctly).",example:"A: Wie zitiere ich richtig?\nB: Name, Jahr, Seitenzahl in der Fussnote.\nA: Und im Literaturverzeichnis?\nB: Dort steht die vollständige Quellenangabe.",exampleSrc:"A: How do I cite correctly?\nB: Name, year, page number in the footnote.\nA: And in the bibliography?\nB: There goes the complete source citation.",funFact:"German citation styles (Chicago, Harvard, APA) are taught in every Proseminar. 'Wer nicht zitiert, plagiiert' (Who does not cite, plagiarizes). The Zitat (quote) must be exact. Even a missing comma can be a problem."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Reihenfolge",src:"the order, the sequence"},{trg:"verfassen",src:"to write, to author"},{trg:"paraphrasieren",src:"to paraphrase"},{trg:"zitieren",src:"to quote, to cite"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"rekonstruieren",src:"to reconstruct",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb. Re- (again) + konstruieren.\n'Ein Argument rekonstruieren' (to reconstruct an argument).",example:"A: Kannst du das Argument des Autors rekonstruieren?\nB: Ja. Er argumentiert in drei Schritten.\nA: Welchen?\nB: These, Begründung, Schlussfolgerung.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you reconstruct the author's argument?\nB: Yes. He argues in three steps.\nA: Which ones?\nB: Thesis, justification, conclusion.",funFact:"Building something again from its pieces. Academic skill: understanding HOW an argument was built. 'Die Rekonstruktion' is the nominalized form. In Hausarbeiten you often must reconstruct other scholars' arguments before critiquing them."},
{type:"teach",trg:"überarbeiten",src:"to revise, to rework",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Über (over) + arbeiten (to work).\n'Den Text überarbeiten' (to revise the text).",example:"A: Wie oft hast du den Text überarbeitet?\nB: Dreimal. Der erste Entwurf ist nie gut genug.\nA: Das klingt nach viel Arbeit.\nB: Überarbeitung ist der wichtigste Schritt.",exampleSrc:"A: How often did you revise the text?\nB: Three times. The first draft is never good enough.\nA: That sounds like a lot of work.\nB: Revision is the most important step.",funFact:"Not separable. Working OVER your text again and again. First draft is never good enough. Die Überarbeitung is where quality lives. German professors expect multiple drafts. 'Überarbeiten Sie den Text' is the most common feedback."},
{type:"teach",trg:"nachweisen",src:"to prove, to demonstrate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Nach (after) + weisen (to show).\nStronger than 'zeigen.'",example:"A: Kann man diese These nachweisen?\nB: Ja, die Daten weisen es eindeutig nach.\nA: Wie?\nB: Durch statistische Analyse.",exampleSrc:"A: Can this thesis be proven?\nB: Yes, the data clearly demonstrate it.\nA: How?\nB: Through statistical analysis.",funFact:"Stronger than 'zeigen' (to show): nachweisen demands evidence. 'Ich weise nach, dass...' (I demonstrate that...). The nominalized form 'der Nachweis' is equally important. Academic German distinguishes between showing and proving."},
{type:"teach",trg:"verweisen",src:"to refer, to cite",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Ver- + weisen (to point).\n'Auf eine Quelle verweisen' (to refer to a source).",example:"A: Auf welche Quelle verweist der Autor?\nB: Er verweist auf eine Studie von 2019.\nA: Ist die Studie zuverlässiig?\nB: Ja, sie wurde in einer Fachzeitschrift publiziert.",exampleSrc:"A: Which source does the author refer to?\nB: He refers to a study from 2019.\nA: Is the study reliable?\nB: Yes, it was published in an academic journal.",funFact:"Not separable. 'Siehe auch...' (See also...) is a Verweis in written form. 'Der Verweis' (the reference) is the noun. Academic texts are networks of Verweise: every claim points to another source."},
{type:"teach",trg:"vertiefen",src:"to deepen, to explore in depth",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Ver- + tiefen (from tief, deep).\nVerbalisierung: adjective 'tief' becomes verb 'vertiefen.'",example:"A: Moechtest du das Thema vertiefen?\nB: Ja, ich will die Analyse vertiefen.\nA: In welche Richtung?\nB: Ich will den theoretischen Rahmen vertiefen.",exampleSrc:"A: Would you like to explore the topic in depth?\nB: Yes, I want to deepen the analysis.\nA: In which direction?\nB: I want to deepen the theoretical framework.",funFact:"Verbalisierung in action: the adjective 'tief' (deep) becomes the verb 'vertiefen' (to deepen). Going below the surface. 'Die Vertiefung' is the nominalized form. Academic work IS Vertiefung: going deeper than the surface allows."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"überarbeiten",src:"to revise, to rework"},{trg:"nachweisen",src:"to prove, to demonstrate"},{trg:"verweisen",src:"to refer, to cite"},{trg:"vertiefen",src:"to deepen, to explore in depth"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"analytisch",src:"analytical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Greek 'analytikos.'\n'Analytisches Denken' (analytical thinking).",example:"A: Was bedeutet analytisch denken?\nB: Probleme in Teile zerlegen und systematisch loesen.\nA: Ist das wichtig im Studium?\nB: Es ist die wichtigste Faehigkeit.",exampleSrc:"A: What does analytical thinking mean?\nB: Breaking problems into parts and solving them systematically.\nA: Is that important in studies?\nB: It is the most important skill.",funFact:"The adjective form of Analyse. 'Ein analytischer Ansatz' (an analytical approach). Required on every German academic CV under 'Faehigkeiten' (skills). Analytical thinking is not just valued: it is expected as baseline competence."},
{type:"teach",trg:"signifikant",src:"significant",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Latin 'significare' (to indicate).\n'Statistisch signifikant' (statistically significant).",example:"A: Sind die Ergebnisse signifikant?\nB: Ja, statistisch signifikant.\nA: Was heißt das genau?\nB: Das Ergebnis ist sehr wahrscheinlich kein Zufall.",exampleSrc:"A: Are the results significant?\nB: Yes, statistically significant.\nA: What does that mean exactly?\nB: The result is very probably not a coincidence.",funFact:"In research, signifikant has a precise meaning: the result is unlikely to be random (p < 0.05). Not just 'important' but 'proven meaningful.' Using 'signifikant' casually is a common mistake that annoys statisticians."},
{type:"teach",trg:"recherchieren",src:"to research, to investigate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"From French 'rechercher'. Active verb for finding sources.\nMore specific than 'forschen': targeted source search.",example:"A: Hast du das Thema gut recherchiert?\nB: Ja, ich habe drei Datenbanken durchsucht.\nA: Wie lange hast du recherchiert?\nB: Fünf Stunden. Gruendliche Recherche braucht Zeit.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you researched the topic well?\nB: Yes, I searched three databases.\nA: How long did you research?\nB: Five hours. Thorough research takes time.",funFact:"Borrowed from French 'rechercher' in the 18th century. More specific than forschen: you recherchieren when actively hunting for sources. Journalists and academics both recherchieren. The noun is 'die Recherche.'"},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Zuerst {1} man die Quellen, dann {2} man die Ergebnisse.",blanks:{"1":"recherchiert","2":"analysiert"},pool:["recherchiert","analysiert","Recherche","Analyse","verfasst","zitiert"],hint:"Two academic verbs: first you search for sources, then you evaluate the results. Both are examples of verbalization."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Plagiat",src:"plagiarism"},{trg:"Fussnote",src:"footnote"},{trg:"Gliederung",src:"outline"},{trg:"Einleitung",src:"introduction"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"warm",art:"de-uni-library-corridor",trg:"Verumius, eine letzte Sache. Die Hausarbeit ist nicht das Ziel. Sie ist das Werkzeug. Du lernst, einen Gedanken bis zum Ende zu verfolgen. Das ist die eigentliche F\u00e4higkeit.",src:"Verumius, one last thing. The term paper is not the goal. It is the tool. You are learning to follow a thought to its conclusion. That is the real skill."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"determined",art:"de-uni-verumius-desk-night",trg:"Zweiundzwanzig Uhr. Die Bibliothek schliesst. Verumius packt seine B\u00fccher ein. Die Gliederung steht. Die Forschungsfrage ist formuliert. H\u00e4tte ihm jemand vor einem Jahr gesagt, dass er eine wissenschaftliche Arbeit auf Deutsch schreiben w\u00fcrde, h\u00e4tte er es f\u00fcr einen schlechten Witz gehalten.",src:"Ten PM. The library closes. Verumius packs his books. The outline is done. The research question is formulated. Had someone told him a year ago that he would write an academic paper in German, he would have taken it for a bad joke."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'die Reihenfolge'?",opts:["the plagiarism","to quote, to cite","the order, the sequence","the diploma thesis"],ans:"the order, the sequence",hint:"Reihe (row) + Folge (succession). Items arranged one after another."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie lange hast du gebraucht, den Text zu {1}?",a:["verfassen"],opts:["verfassen","die Reihenfolge","das Plagiat","paraphrasieren"],hint:"Ver- + fassen (to grasp/compose). To carefully compose a written text.",sSrc:"How long did it take you to write the text?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'paraphrasieren'?",opts:["the plagiarism","to write, to author","to paraphrase","to research, to investigate"],ans:"to paraphrase",hint:"Sounds like its English equivalent. Greek: para (beside) + phrazein (to tell)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to quote, to cite' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["zitieren"],opts:["zitieren","das Plagiat","vertiefen","die Diplomarbeit"],hint:"Cognate of English 'cite.' Latin: citare (to summon as evidence).",sSrc:"How do you say 'to quote, to cite' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'rekonstruieren'?",opts:["to research, to investigate","the bibliography","the footnote","to reconstruct"],ans:"to reconstruct",hint:"Near-identical in English. Re- (again) + construere (to build up anew)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to revise, to rework' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["überarbeiten"],opts:["überarbeiten","der Nachweis","paraphrasieren","analytisch"],hint:"Uber- (over) + arbeiten (to work). To work over a text to improve it.",sSrc:"How do you say 'to revise, to rework' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'verweisen'?",opts:["to refer, to cite","the footnote","the plagiarism","to write, to author"],ans:"to refer, to cite",hint:"Ver- + weisen (to point). To point the reader toward another source."},
{type:"fb",s:"Moechtest du das Thema {1}?",a:["vertiefen"],opts:["die Gliederung","das Literaturverzeichnis","vertiefen","überarbeiten"],hint:"Ver- + tief (deep). To go deeper into a subject or argument.",sSrc:"Would you like to explore the topic in depth?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'analytisch'?",opts:["analytical","the footnote","the diploma thesis","significant"],ans:"analytical",hint:"Greek: analyein (to dissolve into parts). A methodical, logical approach."},
{type:"fb",s:"Sind die Ergebnisse {1}?",a:["signifikant"],opts:["signifikant","die Fussnote","rekonstruieren","verfassen"],hint:"Cognate of English 'significant.' Latin: significare (to point out).",sSrc:"Are the results significant?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'recherchieren'?",opts:["to research, to investigate","the research, the investigation","the footnote","the bibliography"],ans:"to research, to investigate",hint:"French: rechercher (to search again). Thorough, systematic investigation."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l7",title:"Alles unter der Lupe",icon:"🔍",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Alles unter der Lupe",desc:"Test everything from Unit 25. Prove you have mastered academic German, can use Konjunktiv II past, and switch between nominal and verbal style.",goals:["Test everything from Unit 25","Master Konjunktiv II past, Nominalisierung, and Verbalisierung","Navigate academic German confidently"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"focused",art:"de-fub-dahlem-morning",trg:"Fr\u00fcher Morgen, Dahlem. Der Campus liegt still. Verumius sitzt in der leeren Bibliothek. Vor ihm: Karteikarten, Notizen, markierte Textpassagen. Heute ist der Tag, an dem sich zeigt, ob die letzten Wochen Spuren hinterlassen haben.",src:"Early morning, Dahlem. The campus lies quiet. Verumius sits in the empty library. In front of him: flashcards, notes, highlighted text passages. Today is the day that shows whether the last weeks have left their mark."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Forschungsfrage",src:"the research question",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Forschung + Frage.\nThe first thing every Hausarbeit must state.",example:"A: Wie lautet deine Forschungsfrage?\nB: Beeinflusst Nominalisierung die Verständlichkeit?\nA: Das ist eine klare Forschungsfrage.\nB: Ohne Forschungsfrage keine Richtung.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your research question?\nB: Does nominalization affect comprehensibility?\nA: That is a clear research question.\nB: Without a research question, no direction.",funFact:"The first thing every Hausarbeit must state. 'Was ist Ihre Forschungsfrage?' Without one, your paper has no direction. A good Forschungsfrage is specific, answerable, and relevant. It is the compass of your entire paper."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Forschungsergebnis",src:"the research result",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Forschung + Ergebnis.\nPlural: Forschungsergebnisse.",example:"A: Was sind die wichtigsten Forschungsergebnisse?\nB: Nominalisierung reduziert die Lesbarkeit um 30 Prozent.\nA: Ein klares Forschungsergebnis.\nB: Ja, die Daten sind eindeutig.",exampleSrc:"A: What are the most important research results?\nB: Nominalization reduces readability by 30 percent.\nA: A clear research result.\nB: Yes, the data are unambiguous.",funFact:"A compound built from two already-nominalized words: Forschung (from forschen) + Ergebnis (from ergeben). Plural: Forschungsergebnisse. German loves stacking nominalizations. Each layer adds precision."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Fachbereich",src:"the department, the disciplinary area",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Fach (subject) + Bereich (area).\n'Im Fachbereich Linguistik.'",example:"A: In welchem Fachbereich studierst du?\nB: Im Fachbereich Sprach- und Literaturwissenschaft.\nA: Das ist ein grosser Fachbereich.\nB: Ja, mit über 2000 Studierenden.",exampleSrc:"A: In which department do you study?\nB: In the department of linguistics and literature.\nA: That is a large department.\nB: Yes, with over 2000 students.",funFact:"More specific than Fakultaet. A Fachbereich is a subdivision of a Fakultaet. 'Im Fachbereich Linguistik' (in the linguistics department). The organizational unit where your academic life happens daily."},
{type:"fb",s:"Verumius studiert im {1} Sprach- und Literaturwissenschaft.",a:["Fachbereich"],opts:["Fachbereich","Fachgebiet","Rektorat","Hochschule"],hint:"The institutional subdivision of a Fakultaet where your daily academic life happens.",sSrc:"Verumius studies in the department of linguistics and literature."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Fachgebiet",src:"the field of expertise",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. Fach + Gebiet (territory).\n'Mein Fachgebiet ist Computerlinguistik.'",example:"A: Was ist dein Fachgebiet?\nB: Computerlinguistik.\nA: Ein modernes Fachgebiet.\nB: Ja, es verbindet Sprache und Technologie.",exampleSrc:"A: What is your field of expertise?\nB: Computational linguistics.\nA: A modern field.\nB: Yes, it connects language and technology.",funFact:"Your academic territory. Fach (subject) + Gebiet (territory). 'Fachgebiet' implies ownership: this is YOUR area of knowledge. German academics identify strongly with their Fachgebiet. It becomes part of their identity."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Fachsprache",src:"the technical language, the jargon",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Fach + Sprache.\nEvery discipline has its own Fachsprache.",example:"A: Die Fachsprache der Medizin ist schwer.\nB: Ja, viele lateinische Begriffe.\nA: Jedes Fach hat seine eigene Fachsprache.\nB: Linguisten untersuchen sogar die Fachsprache selbst.",exampleSrc:"A: The technical language of medicine is difficult.\nB: Yes, many Latin terms.\nA: Every field has its own technical language.\nB: Linguists even study technical language itself.",funFact:"Every academic discipline has its own Fachsprache. Linguists study Fachsprache itself: meta-language about language. 'Medizinische Fachsprache' (medical jargon), 'juristische Fachsprache' (legal jargon). Each is a language within a language."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Hochschule",src:"the university, the college",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Hoch (high) + Schule (school).\nBroader than Universitaet.",example:"A: Was ist der Unterschied zwischen Universitaet und Hochschule?\nB: Hochschule ist der Oberbegriff.\nA: Also sind alle Universitaeten Hochschulen?\nB: Ja, aber nicht alle Hochschulen sind Universitaeten.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the difference between university and Hochschule?\nB: Hochschule is the umbrella term.\nA: So all universities are Hochschulen?\nB: Yes, but not all Hochschulen are universities.",funFact:"Broader than Universitaet: includes Fachhochschulen (universities of applied sciences). 'Hochschulbildung' (higher education). Germany has over 400 Hochschulen. The word literally means 'high school' but refers to tertiary education, not secondary."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Leistungsnachweis",src:"the certificate of achievement",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Leistung (achievement) + Nachweis (proof).\nProof that you passed a course.",example:"A: Hast du alle Leistungsnachweise?\nB: Mir fehlt noch einer.\nA: Welcher?\nB: Der Leistungsnachweis für das Proseminar.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have all certificates of achievement?\nB: I am still missing one.\nA: Which one?\nB: The certificate for the introductory seminar.",funFact:"You collect Leistungsnachweise like currency: each one counts toward your degree. Without the right Leistungsnachweise, you cannot register for the final exam. German bureaucracy meets academia in this compound noun."},
{type:"teach",trg:"das Rektorat",src:"the office of the university president",pos:"noun",gender:"n",note:"Neuter noun. From Latin 'rector' (ruler).\nThe administrative heart of the university.",example:"A: Wo ist das Rektorat?\nB: Im Hauptgebaeude, dritter Stock.\nA: Was macht man dort?\nB: Dort wird die Universitaetspolitik entschieden.",exampleSrc:"A: Where is the president's office?\nB: In the main building, third floor.\nA: What happens there?\nB: University policy is decided there.",funFact:"Where policy is made. The Rektor or Rektorin is the university president. The Rektorat is their office and the administrative body. 'Im Rektorat vorstellig werden' (to appear at the president's office) is usually not a good sign."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"die Fachsprache",src:"the technical language, the jargon"},{trg:"die Hochschule",src:"the university, the college"},{trg:"der Leistungsnachweis",src:"the certificate of achievement"},{trg:"das Rektorat",src:"the office of the university president"}]},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Wirksamkeit",src:"the effectiveness",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Wirksam (effective) + -keit.\nNominalisierung: adjective to noun.",example:"A: Wie prüft man die Wirksamkeit einer Methode?\nB: Durch empirische Untersuchungen.\nA: Und wenn die Wirksamkeit gering ist?\nB: Dann ändert man die Methode.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you test the effectiveness of a method?\nB: Through empirical investigations.\nA: And if the effectiveness is low?\nB: Then you change the method.",funFact:"Nominalisierung: adjective 'wirksam' (effective) + '-keit' becomes the noun 'Wirksamkeit.' The same pattern: freundlich > Freundlichkeit, zuverlässiig > Zuverlässiigkeit. The '-keit' suffix is productive with '-sam' adjectives."},
{type:"mc",q:"Verumius studiert an einer Hochschule. Was ist eine Hochschule?",opts:["Eine oeffentliche Grundschule fuer Kinder von 6 bis 10 Jahren","Ein Oberbegriff fuer Universitaeten und Fachhochschulen","Ein privater Nachhilfekurs fuer Schueler","Eine Bibliothek"],ans:"Ein Oberbegriff fuer Universitaeten und Fachhochschulen",hint:"'Hoch' (high) + 'Schule' (school). The umbrella term for all institutions of higher education in Germany."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Stichprobe",src:"the random sample",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Stich (stab/prick) + Probe (test/sample).\n'Eine repraesentative Stichprobe.'",example:"A: Wie gross ist deine Stichprobe?\nB: 200 Texte aus fünf Fachbereichen.\nA: Ist das repraesentativ?\nB: Ja, die Stichprobe ist gross genug.",exampleSrc:"A: How large is your sample?\nB: 200 texts from five departments.\nA: Is that representative?\nB: Yes, the sample is large enough.",funFact:"You 'prick' into the data to extract a test portion. A repraesentative Stichprobe must reflect the whole population. Too small, and your results are not signifikant. Too large, and you waste resources. Finding the right Stichprobe is an art."},
{type:"teach",trg:"anwenden",src:"to apply",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. An (on) + wenden (to turn).\n'Methoden anwenden' (to apply methods).",example:"A: Welche Methoden wendest du an?\nB: Qualitative und quantitative Methoden.\nA: Kann man beide gleichzeitig anwenden?\nB: Ja, das nennt man Mixed Methods.",exampleSrc:"A: Which methods do you apply?\nB: Qualitative and quantitative methods.\nA: Can you apply both at the same time?\nB: Yes, that is called mixed methods.",funFact:"Separable: 'Ich wende die Methode an.' You turn (wenden) knowledge toward (an) a problem. 'Die Anwendung' is the nominalized form. Verbalisierung in reverse: the noun Anwendung became the verb anwenden, or perhaps the other way around."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was misst die 'Wirksamkeit' einer Methode?",opts:["Wie schnell sie funktioniert","Wie gut sie das gewuenschte Ergebnis erzielt","Wie gut bekannt und verbreitet sie in der Wissenschaft ist","Wie teuer sie in der Anwendung ist"],ans:"Wie gut sie das gewuenschte Ergebnis erzielt",hint:"From the adjective 'wirksam' (effective) + '-keit'. The noun measures how well something works."},

{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} ist in der Linguistik anders als in der Physik.",a:["Fachsprache"],opts:["Fachsprache","Stichprobe","Methode","Wirksamkeit"],hint:"The specialized vocabulary and terminology used within a particular academic discipline.",sSrc:"The technical language is different in linguistics than in physics."}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l7b",title:"Alles unter der Lupe (Teil 2)",icon:"🔍",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Alles unter der Lupe (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"aufstellen",src:"to set up, to propose",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Auf (up) + stellen (to place).\n'Eine Hypothese aufstellen.'",example:"A: Hast du schon eine Hypothese aufgestellt?\nB: Ja, ich stelle folgende Hypothese auf.\nA: Und wie willst du sie testen?\nB: Durch die Analyse meiner Stichprobe.",exampleSrc:"A: Have you proposed a hypothesis yet?\nB: Yes, I propose the following hypothesis.\nA: And how do you want to test it?\nB: Through the analysis of my sample.",funFact:"You place your idea up for examination. 'Eine These aufstellen' (to put forward a thesis). Separable: 'Ich stelle eine Hypothese auf.' The Aufstellung (setup/proposal) is the nominalized form. Academic German demands that you aufstellen before you beweisen."},
{type:"teach",trg:"belegen",src:"to prove with evidence, to take (a course)",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular verb. Be- + legen (to lay/place).\nDouble meaning in academic contexts.",example:"A: Kannst du deine These belegen?\nB: Ja, drei Studien belegen sie.\nA: Und welche Kurse belegst du?\nB: Semantik und Phonologie.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you substantiate your thesis?\nB: Yes, three studies support it.\nA: And which courses are you taking?\nB: Semantics and phonology.",funFact:"Double meaning: 'Eine These belegen' (to substantiate a thesis with evidence) and 'Einen Kurs belegen' (to enroll in a course). The Beleg (proof/receipt) is the nominalized form. In both cases, you 'lay down' something as proof or claim."},
{type:"teach",trg:"widerlegen",src:"to refute, to disprove",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Inseparable verb. Wider (against) + legen (to lay).\nThe opposite of belegen.",example:"A: Kann man die Hypothese widerlegen?\nB: Ja, wenn die Daten dagegen sprechen.\nA: Ist Widerlegung schlecht?\nB: Nein, auch Widerlegung ist ein Ergebnis.",exampleSrc:"A: Can the hypothesis be refuted?\nB: Yes, if the data speak against it.\nA: Is refutation bad?\nB: No, refutation is also a result.",funFact:"The opposite of belegen. You lay evidence AGAINST a claim. Not separable. 'Die Widerlegung' (refutation) is the nominalized form. In good science, a widerlegt hypothesis is just as valuable as a confirmed one."},
{type:"teach",trg:"zusammenfassen",src:"to summarize",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Zusammen (together) + fassen (to grasp).\n'Die Ergebnisse zusammenfassen.'",example:"A: Kannst du die Ergebnisse zusammenfassen?\nB: Ja, kurz: Nominalisierung senkt die Lesbarkeit.\nA: Gut zusammengefasst.\nB: Die Zusammenfassung steht im letzten Kapitel.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you summarize the results?\nB: Yes, briefly: nominalization reduces readability.\nA: Well summarized.\nB: The summary is in the last chapter.",funFact:"Grasping everything together into one compact form. Separable: 'Ich fasse die Ergebnisse zusammen.' Die Zusammenfassung (summary) is the nominalized form. Every German Hausarbeit ends with a Zusammenfassung. It must be short, precise, and self-contained."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Um eine Hypothese zu testen, muss man {1} sammeln und {2}.",blanks:{"1":"Daten","2":"auswerten"},pool:["Daten","auswerten","Thesen","aufstellen","Methoden","dokumentieren"],hint:"First you gather information, then you systematically analyze it. Two steps of the research process."},
{type:"teach",trg:"evaluieren",src:"to evaluate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb. From French 'evaluer.'\nMore formal than bewerten.",example:"A: Wie evaluiert man ein Lehrprogramm?\nB: Durch Umfragen und Leistungsdaten.\nA: Wer führt die Evaluation durch?\nB: Meist eine externe Kommission.",exampleSrc:"A: How do you evaluate a teaching program?\nB: Through surveys and performance data.\nA: Who conducts the evaluation?\nB: Usually an external committee.",funFact:"More formal than bewerten. Used in institutional contexts: Lehrevaluation (teaching evaluation) happens every semester at German universities. Students rate their professors, and the results are taken seriously. Sometimes."},
{type:"teach",trg:"dokumentieren",src:"to document",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb. From Latin 'documentare.'\n'Ergebnisse dokumentieren.'",example:"A: Hast du alles dokumentiert?\nB: Ja, jeden Schritt der Forschung.\nA: Warum ist Dokumentation so wichtig?\nB: Damit andere die Ergebnisse nachprüfen können.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you document everything?\nB: Yes, every step of the research.\nA: Why is documentation so important?\nB: So others can verify the results.",funFact:"Every step of research must be documented. Die Dokumentation is the nominalized form. In German academia, undocumented work might as well not exist. 'Sorgfaeltige Dokumentation' (careful documentation) is a research fundamental."},
{type:"teach",trg:"differenzieren",src:"to differentiate",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Regular -ieren verb. From Latin 'differentia.'\n'Zwischen Theorie und Praxis differenzieren.'",example:"A: Kann man hier differenzieren?\nB: Ja, man muss zwischen Korrelation und Kausalität differenzieren.\nA: Was ist der Unterschied?\nB: Korrelation heißt nicht Kausalität.",exampleSrc:"A: Can one differentiate here?\nB: Yes, one must differentiate between correlation and causality.\nA: What is the difference?\nB: Correlation does not mean causality.",funFact:"Academic precision: seeing differences others miss. 'Differenzieren zwischen' (to differentiate between). 'Die Differenzierung' is the nominalized form. German academic culture values nuance: the ability to differenzieren separates good scholars from mediocre ones."},
{type:"teach",trg:"hypothetisch",src:"hypothetical",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. From Greek 'hypothesis.'\nKonjunktiv II is the grammar of hypothetische Situationen.",example:"A: Ist das eine reale oder hypothetische Situation?\nB: Hypothetisch. Es ist nicht wirklich passiert.\nA: Welche Grammatik braucht man dafuer?\nB: Den Konjunktiv II.",exampleSrc:"A: Is that a real or hypothetical situation?\nB: Hypothetical. It did not actually happen.\nA: What grammar do you need for that?\nB: The Konjunktiv II.",funFact:"The adjective form of Hypothese. Konjunktiv II past is the grammar of hypothetische Vergangenheit (hypothetical past). 'Hypothetisch gesehen' (hypothetically speaking) frames academic thought experiments."},
{type:"teach",trg:"interdisziplinaer",src:"interdisciplinary",pos:"adj",gender:null,note:"Adjective. Inter- (between) + disziplinaer.\n'Interdisziplinaere Forschung.'",example:"A: Ist deine Forschung interdisziplinaer?\nB: Ja, sie verbindet Linguistik und Informatik.\nA: Das ist modern.\nB: Interdisziplinaere Forschung wird immer wichtiger.",exampleSrc:"A: Is your research interdisciplinary?\nB: Yes, it connects linguistics and computer science.\nA: That is modern.\nB: Interdisciplinary research is becoming ever more important.",funFact:"Working across Fachbereiche. Modern academia values interdisziplinaer collaboration. 'Interdisziplinaere Zusammenarbeit' (interdisciplinary collaboration) is a funding buzzword. The best research often happens at the borders between disciplines."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was beschreibt eine 'hypothetische' Situation?",opts:["Etwas, das sicher passieren wird","Etwas, das tatsaechlich passiert ist","Etwas, das moeglich waere, aber nicht real ist","Etwas, das jeden Tag passiert"],ans:"Etwas, das moeglich waere, aber nicht real ist",hint:"The adjective form of 'Hypothese'. Connected to the grammar of Konjunktiv II."},
{type:"mc",q:"Hätte die Stichprobe groesser sein können, wäre die Wirksamkeit der Methode besser nachgewiesen worden. Welche Merkmale werden kombiniert?",opts:["Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit + Präteritum + Nominalisierung","Nominalisierung + Passiv + Präteritum","Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit + Nominalisierung + Passiv","Präteritum + Nominalisierung + Aktiv"],ans:"Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit + Nominalisierung + Passiv",hint:"'Hätte ... können' and 'wäre ... nachgewiesen worden' are hypothetical past. 'Stichprobe', 'Wirksamkeit', 'Methode' are nouns from verb or adjective stems."},
{type:"fb",s:"Man muss die Hypothese entweder {1} oder widerlegen.",a:["belegen"],opts:["belegen","Beleg","belegt","widerlegt"],hint:"To support a thesis with evidence. The verb that is the direct opposite of 'widerlegen' (to refute).",sSrc:"One must either substantiate or refute the hypothesis."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Zuerst {1} man eine Hypothese, dann versucht man, sie zu {2} oder zu widerlegen.",blanks:{"1":"stellt","2":"belegen"},pool:["stellt","belegen","aufstellt","bewiesen","widerlegen","formuliert"],hint:"The first blank is the separated stem of a separable verb meaning 'to set up or establish'. The prefix lands at the end of the clause."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Stichprobe",src:"random sample"},{trg:"Forschungsfrage",src:"research question"},{trg:"Wirksamkeit",src:"effectiveness"},{trg:"Leistungsnachweis",src:"certificate of achievement"}]},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"satisfied",art:"de-fub-dahlem-campus-afternoon",trg:"Verumius klappt das letzte Buch zu. Er kennt die Begriffe. Er versteht die Muster. H\u00e4tte er das akademische Viertel nicht am ersten Tag erlebt, h\u00e4tte er nie gelernt, dass Wissen in Deutschland seinen eigenen Rhythmus hat.",src:"Verumius closes the last book. He knows the terms. He understands the patterns. Had he not experienced the academic quarter on his first day, he would never have learned that knowledge in Germany has its own rhythm."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'zusammenfassen'?",opts:["to summarize","the field of expertise","the research question","to document"],ans:"to summarize",hint:"Zusammen (together) + fassen (to grasp). Gathering the main points."},
{type:"fb",s:"Wie sagt man 'to evaluate' auf Deutsch? {1}",a:["evaluieren"],opts:["evaluieren","dokumentieren","die Forschungsfrage","das Forschungsergebnis"],hint:"Cognate of English 'evaluate.' Latin: e + valere (to have worth).",sSrc:"How do you say 'to evaluate' in German?"},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'differenzieren'?",opts:["to differentiate","to refute, to disprove","the university, the college","the research result"],ans:"to differentiate",hint:"Near-identical in English. Latin: differentia (a distinguishing quality)."},
{type:"fb",s:"Ist deine Forschung {1}?",a:["interdisziplinaer"],opts:["aufstellen","interdisziplinaer","der Leistungsnachweis","die Hochschule"],hint:"Cognate of English 'interdisciplinary.' Combining multiple academic fields.",sSrc:"Is your research interdisciplinary?"}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l8",title:"Guter Punkt",icon:"🎓",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Guter Punkt",desc:"Verumius presents his research. Yilmaz reflects. Mia and Lukas chime in. Learn final vocabulary, contrast academic and informal register, and celebrate academic milestones.",goals:["Present research in German","Contrast academic and informal register","Celebrate academic milestones and review all constructions"]},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"proud",art:"de-uni-conference-room",trg:"Konferenzraum im Fachbereich. Verumius steht am Rednerpult. Seine Folien sind klar. Seine Gliederung ist deutlich. Er hat diese Praesentation fünfzehn Mal geuebt.",src:"Conference room in the department. Verumius stands at the lectern. His slides are clear. His outline is crisp. He has practiced this presentation fifteen times."},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"confident",art:"de-uni-verumius-presenting",trg:"Die Forschungsfrage meiner Hausarbeit lautet: Wie beeinflusst Nominalisierung die Verständlichkeit akademischer Texte? Anhand einer Stichprobe von 200 Texten habe ich untersucht, ob...",src:"The research question of my term paper is: How does nominalization affect the comprehensibility of academic texts? On the basis of a sample of 200 texts I investigated whether..."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-uni-audience-nod",trg:"Eine Hand geht hoch. Eine Frage. Verumius hält inne, denkt nach, antwortet. Der Professor nickt. Ein Kollege sagt: 'Guter Punkt.'",src:"A hand goes up. A question. Verumius pauses, thinks, answers. The professor nods. A colleague says: 'Good point.'"},
{type:"story",speaker:"yilmaz",mood:"mentoring",art:"de-uni-hallway-yilmaz",trg:"Verumius, das war ausgezeichnet. Hättest du vor zwei Jahren gedacht, dass du so weit kommen würdest?",src:"Verumius, that was excellent. Would you have thought two years ago that you would come this far?"},
{type:"story",speaker:"verumius",mood:"happy",art:"de-uni-verumius-smile",trg:"Nein. Hätte mir jemand das gesagt, hätte ich gelacht. Aber hier bin ich.",src:"No. Had someone told me that, I would have laughed. But here I am."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"warm",art:"de-uni-office-kitchen",trg:"Später. Bueroeküche. Kollegen gratulieren Verumius. Mia schreibt im Gruppenchat.",src:"Later. Office kitchen. Colleagues congratulate Verumius. Mia texts in the group chat."},
{type:"story",speaker:"narrator",mood:"bridge",art:"de-uni-phone-lukas",trg:"Lukas schickt eine Sprachnachricht: 'Der roemische Aquädukt-Vergleich? Typisch Verumius. Übrigens, die Musikschule läuft. Erste Schüler!'",src:"Lukas sends a voice message: 'The Roman aqueduct comparison? Typical Verumius. By the way, the music school is running. First students!'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Umfrage",src:"the survey",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Um (around) + Frage (question).\n'Eine Umfrage durchführen' (to conduct a survey).",example:"A: Hast du eine Umfrage gemacht?\nB: Ja, 150 Studierende haben teilgenommen.\nA: Was hast du gefragt?\nB: Nach ihrer Leseerfahrung mit akademischen Texten.",exampleSrc:"A: Did you conduct a survey?\nB: Yes, 150 students participated.\nA: What did you ask?\nB: About their reading experience with academic texts.",funFact:"You ask questions 'around' a group. Meinungsumfrage (opinion poll) is what news channels love before elections. Online-Umfragen have revolutionized academic research. Die Umfrage is the researcher's workhorse."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Variable",src:"the variable",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. From Latin 'variabilis.'\nAlways feminine in German.",example:"A: Welche Variablen hast du untersucht?\nB: Die abhängige Variable ist Lesbarkeit.\nA: Und die unabhängige?\nB: Der Grad der Nominalisierung.",exampleSrc:"A: Which variables did you investigate?\nB: The dependent variable is readability.\nA: And the independent one?\nB: The degree of nominalization.",funFact:"Statistical terminology borrowed directly from Latin. Always feminine in German. 'Abhängige und unabhängige Variablen' (dependent and independent variables). The foundation of experimental research design."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Datenbank",src:"the database",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Daten (data) + Bank (bench/bank).\n'In der Datenbank suchen.'",example:"A: Wo hast du die Texte gefunden?\nB: In einer linguistischen Datenbank.\nA: Welche Datenbank?\nB: Das Deutsche Referenzkorpus.",exampleSrc:"A: Where did you find the texts?\nB: In a linguistic database.\nA: Which database?\nB: The German Reference Corpus.",funFact:"Where data sits on a 'bench' waiting to be accessed. 'In der Datenbank suchen' (to search the database). Modern research without Datenbanken is unthinkable. The metaphor: data resting on a bank, ready for withdrawal."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Deadline",src:"the deadline",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Borrowed directly from English.\nUsed alongside 'Frist' (deadline/time limit).",example:"A: Wann ist die Deadline?\nB: Nächsten Montag, 23:59 Uhr.\nA: Das ist knapp.\nB: Ja, aber die Deadline ist die Deadline.",exampleSrc:"A: When is the deadline?\nB: Next Monday, 11:59 PM.\nA: That is tight.\nB: Yes, but a deadline is a deadline.",funFact:"Germans use it alongside 'Frist' (deadline/time limit). 'Die Deadline einhalten' (to meet the deadline). One of many English words adopted unchanged into German. The gender is feminine, following the pattern of 'die Frist.'"},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Dozierende",src:"the lecturer (gender-neutral)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine or feminine (der/die Dozierende).\nPresent participle of 'dozieren' used as noun.",example:"A: Wer ist der Dozierende des Seminars?\nB: Frau Dr. Mueller.\nA: Ist sie eine gute Dozierende?\nB: Ja, sehr kompetent und fair.",exampleSrc:"A: Who is the lecturer of the seminar?\nB: Dr. Mueller.\nA: Is she a good lecturer?\nB: Yes, very competent and fair.",funFact:"The modern gender-inclusive alternative to Dozent/Dozentin. Participle used as noun: 'dozierend' (lecturing) becomes 'der/die Dozierende.' Part of the gender-neutral language movement in German academia."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was ist eine 'Variable' in der Forschung?",opts:["Ein fester Wert, der sich nie aendert","Ein veraenderlicher Faktor, den man untersucht","Eine bestimmte Art von Diagramm","Ein bestimmter Abschnitt der Hausarbeit"],ans:"Ein veraenderlicher Faktor, den man untersucht",hint:"From Latin 'variabilis'. In research, the factor that changes and is observed. Always a feminine noun."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Beleg",src:"the evidence, the proof, the receipt",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. From 'belegen' (to prove).\n'Einen Beleg vorlegen' (to present evidence).",example:"A: Hast du einen Beleg für diese These?\nB: Ja, hier ist der Beleg: Seite 47.\nA: Ein klarer Beleg.\nB: Ohne Beleg keine Argumentation.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you have evidence for this thesis?\nB: Yes, here is the proof: page 47.\nA: Clear evidence.\nB: Without proof, no argumentation.",funFact:"In academic writing: a passage that supports your argument. In everyday life: a receipt (Kassenbeleg). The nominalized form of belegen. 'Belege sammeln' (to collect evidence) is what researchers and accountants both do."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Befund",src:"the finding, the result",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Be- + Fund (find/discovery).\n'Der empirische Befund.'",example:"A: Was ist der zentrale Befund deiner Studie?\nB: Nominalisierung erschwert das Verstehen.\nA: Ein wichtiger Befund.\nB: Ja, und er ist statistisch signifikant.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the central finding of your study?\nB: Nominalization makes comprehension harder.\nA: An important finding.\nB: Yes, and it is statistically significant.",funFact:"More specific than Ergebnis: a Befund is what you actually found during investigation. Medical: 'Der aerztliche Befund' (medical findings). Academic: 'Der empirische Befund' (the empirical finding). What the data actually revealed."},
{type:"teach",trg:"der Gegenstand",src:"the object, the subject (of study)",pos:"noun",gender:"m",note:"Masculine noun. Gegen (opposite) + Stand (standing).\n'Der Gegenstand der Untersuchung.'",example:"A: Was ist der Gegenstand deiner Untersuchung?\nB: Die Wirkung von Nominalisierung auf die Lesbarkeit.\nA: Ein klar definierter Gegenstand.\nB: Ja, ohne klaren Gegenstand keine klare Arbeit.",exampleSrc:"A: What is the subject of your investigation?\nB: The effect of nominalization on readability.\nA: A clearly defined subject.\nB: Yes, without a clear subject, no clear paper.",funFact:"What stands before you for examination. 'Der Forschungsgegenstand' (the research subject) is more precise than 'Thema' (topic). The word implies physicality: something standing opposite you, waiting to be examined. Academic German at its most concrete-abstract."},
{type:"teach",trg:"voraussetzen",src:"to presuppose, to require",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Voraus (ahead) + setzen (to set).\n'Grundkenntnisse voraussetzen.'",example:"A: Was setzt dieser Kurs voraus?\nB: Grundkenntnisse in Statistik.\nA: Ich habe keine. Ist das ein Problem?\nB: Ja, der Kurs setzt sie voraus.",exampleSrc:"A: What does this course require?\nB: Basic knowledge of statistics.\nA: I do not have any. Is that a problem?\nB: Yes, the course presupposes it.",funFact:"What must be 'set ahead' before you can proceed. Separable: 'Der Kurs setzt Grundkenntnisse voraus.' 'Die Voraussetzung' (the prerequisite) is the nominalized form. German universities list Voraussetzungen for every course."},
{type:"fb",s:"Um die Ergebnisse zu vergleichen, muss man zwei Theorien {1}.",a:["gegenueberstellen"],opts:["gegenueberstellen","voraussetzen","erwerben","belegen"],hint:"A separable verb meaning to juxtapose. Placing two things opposite each other to see differences.",sSrc:"To compare the results, one must juxtapose two theories."},

{type:"mc",q:"Wir haben eine Umfrage durchgeführt. Was ist 'die Umfrage'?",opts:["the experiment","the survey","the lecture","the hypothesis"],ans:"the survey",hint:"A systematic collection of opinions or data from many people through questions."},

{type:"fb",s:"Alle Ergebnisse sind in der {1} gespeichert.",a:["Datenbank"],opts:["Datenbank","Fachsprache","Stichprobe","Fussnote"],hint:"An organized collection of digital information that can be searched and accessed.",sSrc:"All results are stored in the database."},

{type:"mc",q:"Die Deadline ist morgen. Was ist 'die Deadline'?",opts:["the headline","the deadline","the guideline","the lifeline"],ans:"the deadline",hint:"The final date by which something must be completed. An English loanword used in German."},

{type:"fb",s:"Was ist der {1} deiner Untersuchung?",a:["Gegenstand"],opts:["Gegenstand","Grundlage","Ergebnis","Vorteil"],hint:"The subject or topic that stands before you for examination in research.",sSrc:"What is the subject of your investigation?"}
]},
{id:"deu_r25l8b",title:"Guter Punkt (Teil 2)",icon:"🎓",xp:15,board:true,steps:[
{type:"intro",title:"Guter Punkt (continued)",desc:"Continue practicing the vocabulary from this topic.",goals:["Review and practice key words"]},
{type:"teach",trg:"gegenüberstellen",src:"to compare, to juxtapose",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Separable verb. Gegenüber (opposite) + stellen (to place).\n'Zwei Theorien gegenüberstellen.'",example:"A: Stellst du die zwei Ansaetze gegenüber?\nB: Ja, ich stelle sie im dritten Kapitel gegenüber.\nA: Das ist eine gute Methode.\nB: Durch die Gegenüberstellung werden die Unterschiede klar.",exampleSrc:"A: Do you juxtapose the two approaches?\nB: Yes, I juxtapose them in the third chapter.\nA: That is a good method.\nB: Through the juxtaposition the differences become clear.",funFact:"Placing two things opposite each other to see differences. Separable: 'Ich stelle die Theorien gegenüber.' 'Die Gegenüberstellung' (the juxtaposition) is the nominalized form. A powerful analytical tool in academic writing."},
{type:"teach",trg:"erwerben",src:"to acquire, to obtain",pos:"verb",gender:null,note:"Strong verb: erwarb, erworben. Er- + werben.\n'Kenntnisse erwerben' (to acquire knowledge).",example:"A: Wo hast du diese Faehigkeiten erworben?\nB: Im Studium und durch Praxis.\nA: Man erwirbt viel durch Erfahrung.\nB: Ja, Theorie und Praxis zusammen.",exampleSrc:"A: Where did you acquire these skills?\nB: In my studies and through practice.\nA: One acquires a lot through experience.\nB: Yes, theory and practice together.",funFact:"Strong verb: erwerben/erwarb/erworben. You 'recruit' knowledge to yourself. Formal register. 'Der Erwerb' (the acquisition) is the nominalized form. 'Spracherwerb' (language acquisition) is what Verumius has been doing this entire time."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gleichheit",src:"the equality",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Gleich (equal) + -heit.\nNominalisierung: adjective to noun.",example:"A: Was bedeutet Gleichheit im Grundgesetz?\nB: Alle Menschen sind vor dem Gesetz gleich.\nA: Ist Gleichheit dasselbe wie Gerechtigkeit?\nB: Nein, Gleichheit ist formal, Gerechtigkeit ist inhaltlich.",exampleSrc:"A: What does equality mean in the Basic Law?\nB: All people are equal before the law.\nA: Is equality the same as justice?\nB: No, equality is formal, justice is substantive.",funFact:"Article 3 of the German Grundgesetz guarantees Gleichheit vor dem Gesetz (equality before the law). Nominalisierung: adjective 'gleich' (equal) becomes noun 'Gleichheit.' Same pattern as frei > Freiheit, sicher > Sicherheit."},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'Gerechtigkeit'?",opts:["Vollstaendige Gleichfoermigkeit","Fairness und gleiche Chancen","Strenge gesetzliche Bestrafung","Vollstaendige akademische Freiheit"],ans:"Fairness und gleiche Chancen",hint:"An abstract noun from 'gerecht' (just/fair) + '-igkeit'. A central value in German political discourse."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Gerechtigkeit",src:"the justice",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Gerecht (just/fair) + -igkeit.\nThe -igkeit suffix on consonant-cluster adjectives.",example:"A: Was ist soziale Gerechtigkeit?\nB: Dass alle Menschen faire Chancen haben.\nA: Ist das in Deutschland verwirklicht?\nB: Nicht vollständig. Es bleibt ein Ziel.",exampleSrc:"A: What is social justice?\nB: That all people have fair opportunities.\nA: Is that realized in Germany?\nB: Not completely. It remains a goal.",funFact:"A core value in German political discourse. 'Soziale Gerechtigkeit' (social justice) is a central theme in every Bundestagswahl (federal election). The '-igkeit' suffix on adjectives ending in consonant clusters: gerecht > Gerechtigkeit."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Freiheit",src:"the freedom",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Frei (free) + -heit.\nConstitutionally protected in Germany.",example:"A: Was bedeutet akademische Freiheit?\nB: Forscher dürfen frei forschen und lehren.\nA: Ist das selbstverständlich?\nB: Nein. In vielen Ländern nicht.",exampleSrc:"A: What does academic freedom mean?\nB: Researchers may research and teach freely.\nA: Is that a given?\nB: No. Not in many countries.",funFact:"'Akademische Freiheit' (academic freedom) is constitutionally protected in Germany, Article 5 Grundgesetz. The Berlin Wall's fall was a victory for Freiheit. Nominalisierung: adjective 'frei' becomes noun 'Freiheit.' One of the most powerful words in German."},
{type:"teach",trg:"die Sicherheit",src:"the safety, the security, the certainty",pos:"noun",gender:"f",note:"Feminine noun. Sicher (safe/certain) + -heit.\n'Mit Sicherheit' (with certainty).",example:"A: Kannst du das mit Sicherheit sagen?\nB: Ja, mit hoher Sicherheit.\nA: Wie sicher bist du?\nB: Die Daten geben mir Sicherheit.",exampleSrc:"A: Can you say that with certainty?\nB: Yes, with high certainty.\nA: How sure are you?\nB: The data give me certainty.",funFact:"German values Sicherheit in all its meanings: social security (soziale Sicherheit), job security (Arbeitsplatzsicherheit), certainty of knowledge (Wissenssicherheit). 'Mit Sicherheit' means both 'with certainty' and 'safely.' A culture word."},
{type:"fb",s:"Akademische {1} ist in Deutschland durch Artikel 5 des Grundgesetzes geschuetzt.",a:["Freiheit"],opts:["Freiheit","Sicherheit","Gleichheit","Gerechtigkeit"],hint:"The nominalization of the adjective 'frei' (free) + '-heit'. Constitutionally protected for researchers.",sSrc:"Academic freedom is protected in Germany by Article 5 of the Basic Law."},
{type:"tip",title:"Registerwechsel: Akademisch vs. Informell",text:"Verumius presents: 'Anhand einer Stichprobe von 200 Texten habe ich untersucht, ob die Nominalisierung die Verständlichkeit beeinflusst.'\n\nLukas writes: 'Typisch Verumius.'\n\nThe same person, two worlds. Academic German: Nominalisierung, Konjunktiv, formal connectors (folglich, insbesondere, hinsichtlich). Informal German: short sentences, colloquial language, nicknames.\n\nThe skill is not choosing one style. The skill is mastering both.",deepDive:{title:"Why register switching matters",text:"At university you write 'Die Untersuchung der Daten zeigt signifikante Ergebnisse.' In the group chat you write 'Krasse Ergebnisse!' Both are correct German, but for different contexts. Academic German uses Nominalisierung, Passiv, and formal connectors. Informal German uses active verbs, short sentences, and everyday language."}},
{type:"mc",q:"Yilmaz sagt: 'Hättest du vor zwei Jahren gedacht, dass du so weit kommen würdest?' Was wird hier kombiniert?",opts:["Nur Konjunktiv II der Gegenwart ohne Vergangenheit","Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit + Konjunktiv II Gegenwart","Präteritum als Vergangenheit plus Futur","Nur Konjunktiv II der Vergangenheit, kein Gegenwartsform"],ans:"Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit + Konjunktiv II Gegenwart",hint:"Look for two different time references in the sentence: one looks back at what could have happened, one looks at what would be true now."},
{type:"fb",s:"Die {1} der Forschungsergebnisse bestätigte die Hypothese.",a:["Auswertung"],opts:["Auswertung","Ausgewertet","Auswerten","Wertung"],hint:"Apply the standard -ung nominalization to 'auswerten'. The result is the noun for systematically analyzing data.",sSrc:"The evaluation of the research results confirmed the hypothesis."},
{type:"drag_fill",s:"Auf der {1} dieser Befunde können wir {2}, dass die Methode wirksam ist.",blanks:{"1":"Grundlage","2":"schlussfolgern"},pool:["Grundlage","schlussfolgern","Grund","geschlussfolgert","Schlussfolgerung","folgern"],hint:"On the basis of these results we can conclude that... First a nominalization (basis/foundation), then a verb (to draw a conclusion)."},
{type:"match",pairs:[{trg:"Nominalisierung",src:"making nouns from verbs"},{trg:"Verbalisierung",src:"making verbs from nouns"},{trg:"Konjunktiv II Vergangenheit",src:"hypothetical past"},{trg:"Fussnote",src:"footnote"}]},
{type:"mc",q:"Was bedeutet 'gegenüberstellen'?",opts:["the lecturer (gender-neutral)","the equality","to compare, to juxtapose","the justice"],ans:"to compare, to juxtapose",hint:"Gegen (against) + uber + stellen. To place items side by side."},

{type:"fb",s:"Man muss Erfahrung in der Praxis {1}.",a:["erwerben"],opts:["erwerben","bewerten","anwenden","belegen"],hint:"A formal verb meaning to acquire or obtain through effort. Irregular: erwarb, erworben.",sSrc:"One must acquire experience in practice."}
]}
]};

export default UNIT_25;
